{"entity": "Actinic Keratosis", "type": "concept", "description": "Actinic keratosis is a precancerous skin condition characterized by the development of abnormal, rough, or scaly skin growths. It is primarily caused by long-term exposure to the sun, and its lesions can vary in their specific appearance and color. The condition is clinically significant because it carries a higher risk of progressing into squamous cell carcinoma, a type of skin cancer.\n\nTreatment for actinic keratosis aims to remove these lesions and prevent malignant transformation. Common therapeutic approaches include various topical medications and procedural interventions, with cryotherapy (freezing) being a frequently employed surgical option.<SEP>Actinic keratosis is an area of scaly or rough skin caused by sun exposure that may develop into squamous cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Local Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is usually treated with surgery.<SEP>Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is usually treated with surgery.<SEP>Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes."}
