{"entity": "Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Cancer is a complex and multifaceted disease characterized by the uncontrolled growth and spread of abnormal cells in the body. This fundamental process, driven by genetic mutations, results in cancerous tumors that can crowd out normal cells, impair organ function, and potentially spread to other areas, such as lymph nodes. Cancer can originate in numerous primary locations, including the breast, colon, lungs, prostate, cervix, skin, ovaries, testicles, head and neck, urinary tract, rectum, base of the skull, and lymph nodes. Specific types include invasive breast cancer, cervical cancer, small cell lung cancer, and colon cancer.\n\nDiagnosis and medical planning require determining the cancer's exact type, origin, genetic profile, and stage. This involves diagnostic procedures like biopsy and cystoscopy, imaging tests such as CT, MRI, and PET scans (where MRI is specifically used to check treatment results and see if the cancer has spread), and laboratory and genetic testing. A family history of cancer is a significant risk factor. Cancer itself, along with recent abdominal surgery, is also a recognized risk factor for developing secondary conditions like Deep Vein Thrombosis.\n\nTreatment is highly tailored and may involve a combination of systemic and localized therapies managed by specialists like Medical and Radiation Oncologists. Options include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, immunotherapy, targeted therapy, and chemoradiation, as well as clinical trials. The approach varies; for instance, colon or rectal cancer may necessitate surgical removal, while some cancers are not surgically removable. Treatments can have significant side effects, including damage to reproductive organs affecting fertility, and cause substantial psychological distress such as depression and anxiety. The stress associated with cancer can also make behaviors like quitting smoking more difficult. Comprehensive care therefore integrates supportive measures, palliative care, and management of patient misconceptions about clinical trials to manage symptoms, side effects, and overall well-being. Details about an individual's specific cancer type, treatment, and relevant dates are critical for personal medical management and contact lists.<SEP>A disease that, along with its treatment, can damage and destroy cells in the bone marrow.<SEP>Cancer is a disease where abnormal cells grow, and in the context of the prostate, its risk is assessed using metrics like PSA density and Grade Group.<SEP>The cancer has spread to nearby lymph nodes and is described as metastatic in Stage IV.<SEP>Cancer is a disease that can run in families, and it is important to know its specific type, origin, and spread."}
{"entity": "Regional CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "Regional CSCC, or regional cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, is an advanced form of squamous cell skin cancer characterized by its spread (metastasis) to nearby lymph nodes or tissues. This metastatic progression distinguishes it from localized disease and necessitates a more intensive management strategy.\n\nThe primary and recommended treatment for regional CSCC is surgical removal of the cancerous tissue from the lymph nodes. This is often followed by adjuvant therapy, a combined approach aimed at addressing any residual microscopic disease to improve outcomes. Due to its advanced and metastatic nature, regional CSCC requires more vigilant and frequent post-treatment monitoring compared to localized cancer. This monitoring typically involves regular follow-up physical examinations and imaging tests, such as CT scans, to detect any potential recurrence or further progression at the earliest possible stage."}
