{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It originates in the skin's squamous cells. CSCC occurs more frequently in individuals with lighter skin and is most commonly found on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head and neck. It can also form in scars or chronic wounds, a presentation that can be more difficult to treat.\n\nIn most cases, CSCC can be cured by the complete surgical removal of the tumor. For cases that are more advanced or difficult to treat, management strategies include targeted therapies, immunotherapy, and other forms of systemic therapy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which Mohs surgery is a recommended treatment option.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is a type of skin cancer with low-risk, high-risk, and very high-risk classifications, for which various surgical treatments are recommended."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cells", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cells are a type of thin, flat epithelial cell that constitute the epithelial layer in many tissues throughout the body. Their primary function is to form protective barriers on both external and internal surfaces. A key external location is the upper part of the epidermis, where they form the surface layer of the skin. Internally, they line numerous areas including the mouth, nasopharynx, lower part of the esophagus, lungs, thyroid, anal canal, and the ectocervix.\n\nDue to their location on surfaces exposed to environmental stressors, squamous cells are a common site for the development of cancer. Malignant transformation of these cells leads to squamous cell carcinoma, a major type of cancer. Specific cancers originating from these cells include those of the skin, mouth, esophagus, lungs, and anus. For instance, in conditions like Barrett's esophagus, the normal squamous cell lining of the lower esophagus undergoes abnormal changes, which is a key clinical context for these cells.<SEP>Squamous cells are skin cells on the surface of the epidermis that wear off and are replaced by new cells formed from basal cells.<SEP>Squamous cells are cells on the skin's surface that are replaced by new cells formed from dividing basal cells."}
