{"entity": "DNA", "type": "concept", "description": "DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, is the fundamental genetic material found inside the cells of all living organisms. It is a molecule that contains genes, which are specific segments providing the genetic instructions necessary for an organism's growth, development, and cellular functioning. These DNA molecules are packaged into structures called chromosomes.\n\nDNA carries the genetic information that controls how cells grow and function. This information can be analyzed and copied using various laboratory methods, most notably the Polymerase Chain Reaction (PCR). In medical diagnostics, DNA is extracted from biological samples like blood, skin punch biopsies, or tumor tissue. It is then analyzed through biomarker tests—including FISH, NGS, and PCR—to identify specific mutations, alterations (such as parts of DNA breaking off during a translocation event), and inherited risk factors. Mutations are abnormal changes in the DNA sequence; when they occur, such as from UV radiation damage to skin cells or in cancer cells, they can cause cells to become abnormal and grow uncontrollably.\n\nBeyond its diagnostic role, DNA is also a direct target for several classes of therapeutic drugs. Treatments like anthracyclines disrupt DNA synthesis, hypomethylating agents alter its chemical modifications, and antimetabolites target its molecular building blocks, all aiming to correct or halt disease processes."}
