{"entity": "Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) is a major histological category of cancer that originates in squamous cells, which are thin, flat cells found in the skin and the mucus membranes lining many internal body surfaces. It is not a single disease but a common subtype that can occur in numerous anatomical locations, each with distinct clinical contexts.\n\nIn the context of lung cancer, SCC is a primary subtype of non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC), specifically forming from the flat cells lining the bronchi. Across the head and neck region, SCC is the most common type of throat cancer, including oral, pharyngeal, and nasopharyngeal cancers. It is also the most common type of cervical cancer, forming in the squamous cells lining the ectocervix, and the most common type of anal cancer, originating in the squamous cells of the anal canal. Furthermore, it is a prevalent type of esophageal cancer, particularly common in regions such as Eastern Europe, Asia, and Africa.\n\nStaging for SCC across most cancer sites typically utilizes the TNM system. Specific management guidelines vary by location. For head and neck cancers, p16 testing status is critical for staging. For cervical SCC in early-stage, low-risk disease, it is a criterion for considering extrafascial hysterectomy, and premenopausal patients may be candidates for ovarian transposition before radiation therapy to preserve ovarian function. In other organs, such as the bladder, SCC represents a rare, non-urothelial type of cancer.<SEP>Squamous cell carcinoma is a type of cervical cancer; any grade of this tumor meeting size criteria qualifies for extrafascial hysterectomy.<SEP>Squamous cell carcinoma is a less common, non-urothelial type of bladder cancer.<SEP>The most common type of cervical cancer mentioned in the context of ovarian transposition.<SEP>Squamous cell carcinoma is a subtype of non-small cell lung cancer."}
{"entity": "Actinic Keratosis", "type": "concept", "description": "Actinic keratosis is a precancerous skin condition characterized by the development of abnormal, rough, or scaly skin growths. It is primarily caused by long-term exposure to the sun, and its lesions can vary in their specific appearance and color. The condition is clinically significant because it carries a higher risk of progressing into squamous cell carcinoma, a type of skin cancer.\n\nTreatment for actinic keratosis aims to remove these lesions and prevent malignant transformation. Common therapeutic approaches include various topical medications and procedural interventions, with cryotherapy (freezing) being a frequently employed surgical option.<SEP>Actinic keratosis is an area of scaly or rough skin caused by sun exposure that may develop into squamous cell skin cancer."}
