{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It frequently develops in sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head, neck, and the vermilion lip, and occurs more often in individuals with lighter skin tones.\n\nThe primary and preferred treatment for low-risk cases that have not spread is surgery. Other treatment options include radiation therapy, cryotherapy, and topical therapies. Cases are classified as local when the cancer has not spread to nearby lymph nodes or other sites.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that can be treated by various surgical methods, including curettage and electrodesiccation, PDEMA/Mohs surgery, and standard surgical excision.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is the specific type of squamous cell skin cancer discussed, for which testing and treatment are described."}
{"entity": "Lymphocytes", "type": "concept", "description": "Lymphocytes are a type of white blood cell, or leukocyte, that serves as a central and essential component of the immune system. Their primary function is to fight and prevent infections and diseases. They originate from lymphoid progenitor cells and mature from precursor cells called lymphoblasts. Lymphocytes are produced in the bone marrow and spleen, with T cells maturing in the thymus, and are found throughout the body in the blood, lymph, lymph nodes, and organs.\n\nThe major subtypes are B cells and T cells, which are critical for adaptive immunity. In a healthy state, these cells grow and multiply in a regulated manner in response to infections or inflammation. However, lymphocytes are also the cell of origin for several significant cancers when genetic abnormalities lead to their uncontrolled growth.\n\nThese malignancies include lymphomas, such as Hodgkin lymphoma and Non-Hodgkin lymphoma, which result from the abnormal overgrowth of lymphocytes. They also include leukemias, specifically Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL) and chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL). In ALL, there is an overproduction of immature lymphocytes called lymphoblasts. CLL specifically involves abnormal B lymphocytes. Therefore, while lymphocytes are fundamental for immune defense, their dysregulation is directly linked to these important diseases.<SEP>Lymphocytes are white blood cells that fight infections.<SEP>Lymphocytes are mature white blood cells that develop from lymphoblasts, which come from lymphoid progenitor cells."}
