{"entity": "Scalp", "type": "naturalobject", "description": "The scalp is the skin covering the head. In medical contexts, it is frequently involved in surgical and diagnostic procedures. For instance, during preparation for a stereotactic brain biopsy, a small area of hair on the scalp is shaved or trimmed down and an opening is made in the skin to access the skull. Similarly, in broader brain surgery, the scalp is incised to gain access to the cranial bones.\n\nHealing of the scalp following medical interventions can be particularly problematic. This is specifically noted in cases involving radiation therapy and subsequent surgery. The descriptions highlight that cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) growth on the scalp after radiation treatment presents a significant challenge for successful healing.<SEP>An area of the body where healing after radiation and surgery can be particularly problematic.<SEP>The scalp is a specific area of the body where CSCC is mentioned as being particularly problematic for healing after radiation.<SEP>The scalp is the skin on the head where a small area of hair is shaved and an opening is made for a stereotactic biopsy.<SEP>The scalp is the area where hair is trimmed down to during preparation for a stereotactic biopsy.<SEP>The skin covering the head, which is incised during brain surgery to access the skull.<SEP>The skin on the head where an incision is made during a biopsy procedure."}
