{"entity": "Risk Factor", "type": "concept", "description": "A risk factor is a condition, characteristic, or any element that increases a person's likelihood or chance of developing a disease. It is a broad concept applicable to numerous specific medical conditions. Crucially, the presence of a risk factor elevates probability but does not guarantee disease; individuals with many risk factors may never become ill, while others with none may still be affected.\n\nRisk factors encompass a diverse range of elements, including behavioral, environmental, infectious, demographic, and genetic components. Concrete examples across various cancers illustrate this diversity. For lung cancer, a primary risk factor is smoking tobacco. For skin cancers, risk factors include sun exposure for squamous cell skin cancer and other factors associated with basal cell skin cancer. For liver cancer, established risk factors include cirrhosis and chronic hepatitis B. Other specific examples include having a reduced immune system for primary CNS lymphoma, and various factors associated with bladder, thyroid, and anal cancers.\n\nBeyond specific exposures, broader demographic and inherited elements are also significant risk factors. These include age, family history, genetic factors, and race. Furthermore, for certain diseases like squamous cell skin cancer, specific risk factors such as the lesion's location and size are used clinically to determine the disease's risk level.<SEP>A risk factor is something that increases the risk of developing a disease, such as cervical cancer.<SEP>A risk factor is anything that increases a person's chance of getting cancer, including prostate cancer."}
