{"entity": "Basal Cells", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cells are a type of cell located in the basal cell layer, which is the lowest part of the epidermis. Their primary function is to constantly divide through mitosis, generating new cells. These new cells serve to replace the squamous cells on the skin's surface that are worn off through normal shedding. As these newly formed basal cells mature and move upward through the epidermal layers, they themselves differentiate and become squamous cells. This continuous cycle of cell division and differentiation is essential for skin renewal and repair. Furthermore, basal cells are clinically significant because basal cell skin cancer, a common form of skin cancer, originates when these cells undergo abnormal, uncontrolled growth.<SEP>Basal cells are cells found in the lower part of the epidermis that constantly divide to form new cells, replacing squamous cells on the skin's surface."}
{"entity": "Fair Skin", "type": "concept", "description": "A physical characteristic that is a risk factor for basal cell skin cancer, as lighter-colored skin has less protective melanin.<SEP>Fair skin is a physical characteristic that increases the risk of developing basal cell skin cancer due to lower melanin levels.<SEP>A physical characteristic that is a risk factor for basal cell skin cancer, as lighter-colored skin has less protective melanin.<SEP>Fair skin is a physical characteristic that increases the risk of developing basal cell skin cancer due to lower melanin levels.<SEP>Fair skin is a risk factor for basal cell skin cancer, as lighter-colored skin has less protective melanin."}
{"entity": "Lymph Nodes", "type": "naturalobject", "description": "Lymph nodes are small, bean-shaped anatomical structures that serve as key organs of the body's lymphatic and immune systems. They are distributed throughout the body, notably in regions such as the neck, underarms (axillae), groin, chest, abdomen, and pelvis. Their primary physiological functions are to filter lymphatic fluid, produce and house infection-fighting immune cells like lymphocytes, and remove foreign material. Clinically, they are often checked during physical examinations for enlargement, which can indicate infection or disease.\n\nIn oncology, lymph nodes are critically important. They are common sites for the metastatic spread of many solid tumors, including breast, prostate, bladder, lung, stomach, ovarian, colon, and cutaneous squamous cell (CSCC) cancers. The involvement of lymph nodes defines more advanced disease stages and is a key factor in cancer staging, prognosis, and treatment planning across multiple systems, including the TNM staging system (where it is the 'N' category) and the FIGO staging system for gynecological cancers. Lymph nodes are also primary sites for the development of lymphomas, such as Diffuse Large B-Cell Lymphoma and Follicular Lymphoma. In B-cell lymphoblastic lymphoma, malignant B-cell lymphoblasts grow predominantly within the nodes.\n\nDiagnostically, lymph nodes near a tumor are often surgically removed during procedures like a colectomy or transabdominal surgery and sent to a laboratory for pathological examination to test for cancer spread. Assessment also involves imaging techniques such as ultrasound, CT, MRI, and FDG-PET/CT. Therapeutically, if cancerous nodes are found, they may be surgically removed or targeted with treatments like external beam radiation therapy. In specific cancers like thyroid cancer, spread to lymph nodes is a factor in recommending adjuvant therapies like radioactive iodine (RAI). Thus, lymph nodes serve as defensive immune organs, critical prognostic indicators, diagnostic samples, and direct treatment targets across a wide spectrum of malignancies.<SEP>Bean-shaped glands found throughout the body that contain immune cells; they may be removed during cervical cancer surgery.<SEP>Lymph nodes are part of the lymphatic system and are assessed to see if cancer has spread to them.<SEP>Lymph nodes are small structures that help fight disease; cancer spread to them is a factor in staging pancreatic cancer.<SEP>Lymph nodes are structures that can be invaded by stomach cancer cells, particularly those near the stomach in locoregional cancer or distant nodes in metastatic cancer.<SEP>Glands in the neck, underarm, and groin that are checked for enlargement during a physical exam.<SEP>Nearby lymph nodes are sites to which the cancer has spread."}
