{"entity": "Risk Factors", "type": "concept", "description": "Risk factors are characteristics, activities, environmental exposures, or inherited traits that increase a person's chance of developing a specific disease, such as cancer. They are distinct from a direct cause, as their presence does not guarantee the disease will occur. Common categories include lifestyle choices (e.g., smoking), environmental elements (e.g., chemical exposures), demographic traits (e.g., older age), personal health conditions, and family history or genetic predisposition. These factors vary significantly by cancer type. For instance, UV light exposure, fair skin, and light eye color are primary risk factors for basal cell skin cancer, while smoking is a major risk factor for lung cancer. Similarly, specific lifestyle, chemical exposure, health conditions, and family history are associated with pancreatic cancer, and age and family history are key factors for prostate cancer. Risk factors for liver cancer also fall into these general categories of activities, environmental elements, and inherited traits.\n\nIn a separate but related clinical context, the term \"risk factors\" also refers to specific pathological or clinical features of a diagnosed cancer itself. These are characteristics, such as tumor size, lymphovascular space invasion (LVSI), or surgical margin status, which oncologists evaluate to estimate the likelihood of cancer recurrence. This assessment directly informs treatment decisions, such as whether to recommend external beam radiation therapy (EBRT) after surgery.\n\nFurthermore, patient-specific characteristics like age and overall health status are considered risk factors that influence the selection of treatment options and predicted outcomes, bridging the concepts of disease development and post-diagnosis management.<SEP>Elements that increase the likelihood of developing prostate cancer, such as age and family history, though they do not directly cause the disease.