{"entity": "Melanin", "type": "concept", "description": "Melanin is a pigment produced by specialized cells called melanocytes. Its primary biological functions are to determine the color of an individual's skin, hair, and eyes. A critically important secondary function is to provide protection against the harmful effects of ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun. Melanin acts as a natural filter, absorbing and scattering UV rays to shield skin cells from damage. Consequently, individuals with lower levels of melanin have less natural protection and are at a higher risk for developing skin cancer due to UV exposure.<SEP>Melanin is the skin pigment that filters out the sun's harmful UV rays, providing protection against skin cancer.<SEP>Melanin is a substance created in the epidermis that is responsible for skin color.<SEP>Melanin is a pigment produced by melanocytes responsible for the color of hair, skin, and eyes and provides protection against ultraviolet (UV) rays.<SEP>Melanin is a pigment produced by melanocytes that is responsible for hair, skin, and eye color and protects skin from harmful ultraviolet (UV) rays."}
