{"entity": "Age", "type": "concept", "description": "Age is a fundamental and significant risk factor across multiple types of cancer, most prominently for prostate cancer. For prostate cancer, age is consistently identified as the leading or biggest risk factor, with the likelihood of developing the disease increasing substantially as one gets older. Diagnosis is most common in individuals aged 65 years and above. In clinical practice, a patient's age is a critical component used alongside Prostate-Specific Antigen (PSA) test results, digital rectal exam findings, family history, and race to assess individual risk and to determine the need for further diagnostic procedures, such as a biopsy. Age also directly influences the interpretation of PSA levels in screening, with higher levels generally considered more suspicious for cancer in older individuals.\n\nBeyond prostate cancer, age is a recognized risk factor for other malignancies. The risk of bladder cancer increases as a person gets older. Similarly, for basal cell skin cancer, advancing age represents a key risk factor, largely due to the cumulative lifetime exposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun. Furthermore, a patient's age is utilized by doctors as one factor in assessing the likelihood of hereditary ovarian cancer. Overall, age serves as a fundamental epidemiological and clinical variable in oncology, informing risk assessment and diagnostic pathways across multiple cancer types."}
