{"entity": "Actinic Keratosis", "type": "concept", "description": "Actinic keratosis is a precancerous skin condition characterized by the development of abnormal, rough, or scaly skin growths. It is primarily caused by long-term exposure to the sun, and its lesions can vary in their specific appearance and color. The condition is clinically significant because it carries a higher risk of progressing into squamous cell carcinoma, a type of skin cancer.\n\nTreatment for actinic keratosis aims to remove these lesions and prevent malignant transformation. Common therapeutic approaches include various topical medications and procedural interventions, with cryotherapy (freezing) being a frequently employed surgical option.<SEP>Actinic keratosis is an area of scaly or rough skin caused by sun exposure that may develop into squamous cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It frequently develops in sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head, neck, and the vermilion lip, and occurs more often in individuals with lighter skin tones.\n\nThe primary and preferred treatment for low-risk cases that have not spread is surgery. Other treatment options include radiation therapy, cryotherapy, and topical therapies. Cases are classified as local when the cancer has not spread to nearby lymph nodes or other sites.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that can be treated by various surgical methods, including curettage and electrodesiccation, PDEMA/Mohs surgery, and standard surgical excision.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is the specific type of squamous cell skin cancer discussed, for which testing and treatment are described."}
{"entity": "Actinic Keratoses", "type": "concept", "description": "Actinic keratoses are pre-cancerous skin lesions characterized by scaly or rough patches. They are primarily caused by prolonged exposure to the sun. If left untreated, these lesions have the potential to develop into squamous cell carcinoma, a form of skin cancer.\n\nThe management of actinic keratoses typically involves superficial treatments aimed at removing the damaged cells. Common and effective treatment options include cryotherapy (freezing), photodynamic therapy, and various topical therapies."}
