{"entity": "CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "CSCC, or Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma, is a form of squamous cell skin cancer. It is a type of skin cancer that can metastasize and is characterized by varying risk levels, including low-risk forms and very high-risk local disease. A specific risk factor is its potential to grow in previously radiated areas of the skin.\n\nTreatment for CSCC is tailored based on its risk assessment. Surgical options are prominent, with Mohs micrographic surgery being a preferred treatment for very high-risk local tumors. Non-surgical treatments are also utilized, including radiation therapy (using electrons and photons), systemic therapies like the EGFR inhibitor Cetuximab, and PD-1 inhibitors. The choice of treatment, whether surgical or non-surgical, is recommended according to the cancer's risk level. A noted specific risk of treatment, particularly when the cancer is located near the eye, is the potential development of cataracts from radiation therapy.<SEP>CSCC is a type of cancer that can be treated with radiation therapy methods like EBRT and brachytherapy.<SEP>CSCC refers to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, a type of squamous cell skin cancer that may be treated with systemic therapy and radiation."}
{"entity": "Melanin", "type": "concept", "description": "Melanin is a pigment produced by specialized cells called melanocytes. Its primary biological functions are to determine the color of an individual's skin, hair, and eyes. A critically important secondary function is to provide protection against the harmful effects of ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun. Melanin acts as a natural filter, absorbing and scattering UV rays to shield skin cells from damage. Consequently, individuals with lower levels of melanin have less natural protection and are at a higher risk for developing skin cancer due to UV exposure.<SEP>Melanin is the skin pigment that filters out the sun's harmful UV rays, providing protection against skin cancer.<SEP>Melanin is a substance created in the epidermis that is responsible for skin color.<SEP>Melanin is a pigment produced by melanocytes responsible for the color of hair, skin, and eyes and provides protection against ultraviolet (UV) rays.<SEP>Melanin is a pigment produced by melanocytes that is responsible for hair, skin, and eye color and protects skin from harmful ultraviolet (UV) rays."}
{"entity": "High-Risk CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "High-Risk CSCC is a classification of cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC), a type of squamous cell skin cancer. This category is defined by specific pathological features that indicate an increased risk of local recurrence and metastasis compared to low-risk disease, necessitating different treatment approaches. One key pathological feature that can determine this high-risk classification is perineural invasion, where the tumor has grown into nerves. A standard and recommended treatment option for high-risk CSCC is surgical excision."}
