{"entity": "Regional CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "Regional CSCC, or regional cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, is an advanced form of squamous cell skin cancer characterized by its spread (metastasis) to nearby lymph nodes or tissues. This metastatic progression distinguishes it from localized disease and necessitates a more intensive management strategy.\n\nThe primary and recommended treatment for regional CSCC is surgical removal of the cancerous tissue from the lymph nodes. This is often followed by adjuvant therapy, a combined approach aimed at addressing any residual microscopic disease to improve outcomes. Due to its advanced and metastatic nature, regional CSCC requires more vigilant and frequent post-treatment monitoring compared to localized cancer. This monitoring typically involves regular follow-up physical examinations and imaging tests, such as CT scans, to detect any potential recurrence or further progression at the earliest possible stage."}
