{"entity": "BRCA2", "type": "concept", "description": "BRCA2 is a human gene that functions as a critical tumor suppressor, primarily involved in DNA repair. Inherited, or germline, mutations in the BRCA2 gene significantly increase an individual's lifetime risk for developing several specific cancers. These notably include breast cancer, ovarian cancer, prostate cancer, pancreatic cancer, and melanoma.\n\nDue to this established hereditary risk, BRCA2 is a primary gene examined in germline genetic testing for individuals with a personal or strong family history of these cancers. Furthermore, because of its fundamental role in DNA repair, the BRCA2 gene is also analyzed in tumor testing to identify specific somatic abnormalities. The presence of such abnormalities in a tumor can inform treatment decisions, making BRCA2 status a key biomarker for both hereditary cancer predisposition and therapeutic strategy.<SEP>BRCA2 is a gene involved in DNA repair that is tested for abnormalities.<SEP>BRCA2 is a gene in which germline mutations can increase the risk of prostate cancer and other cancers.<SEP>BRCA2 is an inherited gene mutation related to breast cancer, ovarian cancer, pancreatic cancer, and skin cancer (melanoma)."}
{"entity": "Risk Factors", "type": "concept", "description": "Risk factors are characteristics, activities, environmental exposures, or inherited traits that increase a person's chance of developing a specific disease, such as cancer. They are distinct from a direct cause, as their presence does not guarantee the disease will occur. Common categories include lifestyle choices (e.g., smoking), environmental elements (e.g., chemical exposures), demographic traits (e.g., older age), personal health conditions, and family history or genetic predisposition. These factors vary significantly by cancer type. For instance, UV light exposure, fair skin, and light eye color are primary risk factors for basal cell skin cancer, while smoking is a major risk factor for lung cancer. Similarly, specific lifestyle, chemical exposure, health conditions, and family history are associated with pancreatic cancer, and age and family history are key factors for prostate cancer. Risk factors for liver cancer also fall into these general categories of activities, environmental elements, and inherited traits.\n\nIn a separate but related clinical context, the term \"risk factors\" also refers to specific pathological or clinical features of a diagnosed cancer itself. These are characteristics, such as tumor size, lymphovascular space invasion (LVSI), or surgical margin status, which oncologists evaluate to estimate the likelihood of cancer recurrence. This assessment directly informs treatment decisions, such as whether to recommend external beam radiation therapy (EBRT) after surgery.\n\nFurthermore, patient-specific characteristics like age and overall health status are considered risk factors that influence the selection of treatment options and predicted outcomes, bridging the concepts of disease development and post-diagnosis management.<SEP>Elements that increase the likelihood of developing prostate cancer, such as age and family history, though they do not directly cause the disease.<SEP>Variables that increase the likelihood of developing a disease or experiencing a poor outcome.<SEP>Characteristics such as tumor size and the presence of LVSI that a doctor considers when determining the need for post-surgery EBRT.<SEP>Risk factors are elements that increase the likelihood of developing squamous cell skin cancer, listed as a section in the guide."}
{"entity": "BRCA1", "type": "concept", "description": "BRCA1 is a human gene that plays a critical role in DNA repair. Inherited, or germline, mutations in this gene significantly increase an individual's lifetime risk for developing several types of cancer. The cancers most strongly associated with BRCA1 mutations include breast cancer, ovarian cancer, and prostate cancer. Additionally, mutations are linked to an elevated risk for pancreatic cancer and melanoma.\n\nDue to these established hereditary cancer links, BRCA1 is a primary gene examined in germline genetic testing. This is particularly relevant for individuals with a personal or family history of the associated cancers. Furthermore, because of its fundamental function in DNA repair, the BRCA1 gene is also analyzed in tumor testing to identify specific abnormalities that can inform treatment decisions.<SEP>BRCA1 is a gene involved in DNA repair that is tested for abnormalities.<SEP>BRCA1 is a gene in which germline mutations can increase the risk of prostate cancer and other cancers.<SEP>BRCA1 is an inherited gene mutation related to breast cancer, ovarian cancer, pancreatic cancer, and skin cancer (melanoma)."}
{"entity": "Risk Factor", "type": "concept", "description": "A risk factor is a condition, characteristic, or any element that increases a person's likelihood or chance of developing a disease. It is a broad concept applicable to numerous specific medical conditions. Crucially, the presence of a risk factor elevates probability but does not guarantee disease; individuals with many risk factors may never become ill, while others with none may still be affected.\n\nRisk factors encompass a diverse range of elements, including behavioral, environmental, infectious, demographic, and genetic components. Concrete examples across various cancers illustrate this diversity. For lung cancer, a primary risk factor is smoking tobacco. For skin cancers, risk factors include sun exposure for squamous cell skin cancer and other factors associated with basal cell skin cancer. For liver cancer, established risk factors include cirrhosis and chronic hepatitis B. Other specific examples include having a reduced immune system for primary CNS lymphoma, and various factors associated with bladder, thyroid, and anal cancers.\n\nBeyond specific exposures, broader demographic and inherited elements are also significant risk factors. These include age, family history, genetic factors, and race. Furthermore, for certain diseases like squamous cell skin cancer, specific risk factors such as the lesion's location and size are used clinically to determine the disease's risk level.<SEP>A risk factor is something that increases the risk of developing a disease, such as cervical cancer.<SEP>A risk factor is anything that increases a person's chance of getting cancer, including prostate cancer."}
