{"entity": "Melanoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Melanoma is a type of skin cancer. It is distinct from and less common than other major forms like basal cell carcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma, but it is notably more aggressive. Information for patients regarding this condition is available in the NCCN Guidelines for Patients.\n\nThe development of melanoma has significant genetic and familial risk associations. Inherited germline mutations in genes, including BRCA1 and BRCA2, are identified as factors that increase an individual's risk. Furthermore, familial history plays a role; having a close blood relative with a history of melanoma is itself recognized as a risk factor for developing pancreatic cancer."}
{"entity": "BRCA Genes", "type": "concept", "description": "BRCA genes are genes that all individuals possess. Their normal, healthy function is to repair damaged DNA, help cells grow normally, and, crucially, to prevent tumor growth by maintaining genomic stability. When inherited in a mutated form, these genes significantly increase a person's lifetime risk of developing several cancers, most notably breast and ovarian cancer, but also others such as prostate and pancreatic cancer.\n\nIn the context of cancer treatment, mutations in BRCA genes within tumor tissue itself serve as a critical biomarker. Specifically for ovarian cancer, testing tumor tissue for these mutations is a standard and important procedure. The presence of such a mutation can guide treatment planning, as it may indicate a tumor's susceptibility to certain targeted therapies, such as PARP inhibitors. Therefore, BRCA gene status is assessed both for hereditary cancer risk via germline testing and for therapeutic decision-making via somatic testing of the tumor.<SEP>Genes that repair damaged cells; mutations in these genes increase the risk of developing ovarian, breast, and other cancers.<SEP>BRCA genes are genes that, when mutated, are important in DNA repair and should be tested for in ovarian cancer tumors.<SEP>BRCA genes are genes that, when mutated in a tumor, are an important biomarker for ovarian cancer treatment planning.<SEP>Normal BRCA genes help prevent tumor growth, fix damaged cells, and help cells grow normally.<SEP>BRCA genes are associated with hereditary ovarian cancer risk and are tested for in genetic testing."}
