{"entity": "Hereditary Ovarian Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Hereditary Ovarian Cancer is a form of ovarian cancer caused by inherited genetic mutations passed from parent to child. The condition is most frequently associated with mutations in specific genes, notably BRCA1 and BRCA2. It is also linked to Lynch syndrome, a hereditary condition that predisposes individuals to various cancers.\n\nA key characteristic of hereditary ovarian cancer is that it typically manifests at a younger age compared to non-hereditary (sporadic) cases of the disease. This earlier onset is a direct consequence of the inherited genetic predisposition."}
{"entity": "Family History", "type": "concept", "description": "Family History is a comprehensive record of the health conditions, diseases, and causes of death present among a person's blood relatives. It is fundamental information about a person's family medical background and ancestry, collected by healthcare teams, including doctors and genetic counselors. This information encompasses the health of close relatives on both sides of the family, including specific details about diseases such as cancer, heart disease, and diabetes, the age at which relatives were diagnosed, the results of any genetic testing, and the overall pattern of illness.\n\nIn clinical practice, family history is a critical personal risk factor used to assess an individual's inherited risk for hereditary diseases, including various cancers and other conditions. For cancer specifically, having a close relative with cancers like prostate, thyroid, or bladder cancer significantly increases an individual's personal risk for those diseases. A family history of cancer or specific gene mutations is also a key factor in considering inherited genetic testing. This risk assessment directly impacts care planning, treatment decisions, and personalized screening recommendations. For instance, in prostate cancer screening, family history is considered alongside factors like race, age, and exam findings. Similarly, family history is a factor in assessing risk and planning treatment for conditions like chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL).\n\nIt is important to note that many cases of diseases, including various cancers, can be sporadic without a clear familial link. Ultimately, synthesizing family history allows healthcare teams to estimate the probability of developing specific conditions, thereby informing clinical judgment, preventive health strategies, and health screening protocols.<SEP>Information about the health history of a patient's blood relatives, used to assess cancer risk.<SEP>A family history reflects patterns of certain diseases, including prostate and other cancers, among family members, which can increase individual risk.<SEP>Family history is information about the health history of blood relatives, including diseases like cancer, heart disease, and diabetes."}
