{"entity": "Head And Neck Cancers", "type": "concept", "description": "Head and neck cancers are a group of cancers that originate in the head or neck area of the body, named and treated based on the specific anatomical site of the tumor. These sites include the mouth, oropharynx, nasal cavity, nasopharynx, larynx, and hypopharynx, encompassing specific types such as mouth cancer and throat cancer. The vast majority are squamous cell carcinomas.\n\nA primary and modifiable risk factor is a history of smoking or vaping nicotine. Quitting is considered essential both to maximize the chances of a cure and to minimize treatment-related side effects. Certain types, particularly some oropharyngeal cancers, are also caused by human papillomavirus (HPV), placing them in a category shared with other HPV-related cancers.\n\nWhile head and neck cancers are generally not inherited from biological parents, a family history of other cancers can sometimes inform individual risk assessment, indicating potential familial risk factors. A common characteristic of these cancers is their potential to spread, often to the lymph nodes in the neck.<SEP>For head and neck cancers, stopping smoking or vaping is essential to maximize the chance for cure and minimize side effects.<SEP>Head and neck cancers are a group of cancers originating in the head or neck area of the body.<SEP>Head and neck cancers are types of cancer that can sometimes spread to the lymph nodes in the neck.<SEP>Head and neck cancers are specific types of cancer where quitting smoking or vaping is essential to maximize cure chances and minimize side effects."}
