{"entity": "Germline Mutations", "type": "concept", "description": "Germline mutations are inherited genetic changes present in every cell of an individual's body from birth. They are passed down from biological (or birth) parents and can be transmitted to one's own children. These mutations are specifically sought and identified through genetic testing, often referred to as germline testing or genetic cancer risk testing.\n\nA key characteristic of germline mutations is their association with an increased, heritable risk for developing certain diseases, most notably various types of cancer. They represent an inherited predisposition, meaning they are not acquired during a person's lifetime. Specific genes in which these mutations are commonly found include CDKN2A, FGFR3, PIK3CA, ERBB, and BRCA genes, among others. The identification of a germline mutation through testing can therefore indicate a heightened risk for cancer.<SEP>Inherited mutations that occur in every cell in the body and are the target of genetic testing for inherited cancer risk."}
