{"entity": "Basal Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer. It is caused by damage to the DNA of basal cells, primarily from exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources. While it can occur in anyone, it is most frequently diagnosed in individuals with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, making fair skin a significant risk factor.

This cancer is characterized by its high treatability and curability, especially when detected and addressed early. A key clinical feature is that it rarely metastasizes, or spreads to other parts of the body. Accurate diagnostic testing is essential for confirming the diagnosis and for informing appropriate treatment planning.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a highly treatable and curable form of skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer, often treatable and curable when caught early.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can happen to anyone but is most common in people with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, with specific lesion appearances."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell skin cancer, also known as cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC), is the second most common type of skin cancer. It is highly treatable and often curable. This cancer typically begins as scaly patches on the skin and can develop from pre-cancerous lesions called actinic keratoses. It is most frequently caused by cumulative sun exposure over many years, with other major risk factors including indoor tanning and exposure to environmental toxins. It can also form within old wounds, burns, or scars.

Diagnosis is confirmed through a skin biopsy. The disease is classified as local, regional, or metastatic, with the potential to spread to nearby lymph nodes. Treatment depends on the cancer's extent and risk classification. Primary treatments are surgical, including Mohs surgery and standard excision, often with lymph node assessment. Other options include radiation therapy and topical treatments. For advanced cases, systemic therapies such as chemotherapy, EGFR inhibitors, and PD-1 inhibitors are used.

Given its risk of recurrence and the increased risk of developing other skin cancers, patients require specific follow-up monitoring schedules after treatment, particularly for local and regional forms of the disease.<SEP>Squamous cell skin cancer is a type of cancer that can be treated with systemic therapy, including PD-1 inhibitors.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which a weakened immune system is a risk factor, requiring regular screening and diagnosis via biopsy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer; recurrent tumors of this type are considered high-risk, and it can start in areas of damaged skin."}
