{"entity": "Anal Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Anal cancer is an uncommon type of cancer of the digestive system that originates in the anal canal or perianal region. It typically begins as pre-cancerous lesions or abnormal cells, with its earliest form known as SISCCA, progressing to invasive anal cancer at more advanced stages. The disease most often starts in the squamous cells lining the anal canal, making squamous cell carcinoma the most common type. A primary cause is infection with the human papillomavirus (HPV), and individuals with HIV are at an increased risk.

