For most non-metastatic cases, the standard recommended treatment is chemoradiation, which combines radiation therapy and chemotherapy. This treatment is a specific focus of patient inquiries. If the cancer does not respond to initial therapy or recurs, surgical options like Abdominoperineal Resection (APR) may be required. The disease and its treatments can lead to various physical and mental health side effects.

Following treatment, anal cancer requires ongoing survivorship care and specific surveillance protocols, as the cancer can progress, go into remission, or recur. Survivors, who are the primary audience for survivorship guidelines, often experience specific long-term physical and psychological effects.<SEP>Anal cancer is a disease where imaging tests are used to learn its extent in the anus, pelvis, and distant areas like the liver or lungs.<SEP>Anal cancer is a disease that is staged based on tumor size, lymph node involvement, and metastasis."}
{"entity": "Nonmelanoma Skin Cancers", "type": "concept", "description": "Nonmelanoma skin cancers, or keratinocyte carcinomas, refer to basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers that behave differently from melanoma.<SEP>Nonmelanoma skin cancers, or keratinocyte carcinomas, refer to basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers that behave differently from melanoma.<SEP>Nonmelanoma skin cancers, also called keratinocyte carcinomas, is a category that includes basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers because they do not behave like melanoma."}
{"entity": "Immunosuppressants", "type": "artifact", "description": "Immunosuppressants are a class of drugs primarily administered following an organ transplant to prevent the recipient's immune system from rejecting the new organ. Their fundamental mechanism of action involves weakening or suppressing the body's immune response. A significant consequence of this therapeutic effect is an increased risk of certain infections and cancers due to the compromised immune surveillance. Specifically, the use of immunosuppressants is associated with an elevated risk of developing anal cancer.<SEP>Drugs taken after organ transplantation to prevent organ rejection, which also reduce the body's ability to fight infection and disease."}
{"entity": "CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "CSCC, or Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma, is a form of squamous cell skin cancer. It is a type of skin cancer that can metastasize and is characterized by varying risk levels, including low-risk forms and very high-risk local disease. A specific risk factor is its potential to grow in previously radiated areas of the skin.

