{"entity": "Human Immunodeficiency Virus", "type": "concept", "description": "Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is a viral infection that weakens the human immune system. This immunosuppression is a significant risk factor for several types of cancer. Specifically, HIV infection increases the risk of squamous cell skin cancer, also referred to as cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC). Furthermore, it is a documented risk factor for anal cancer. The repeated conflation of HIV with AIDS in some descriptions reflects the progression of the untreated infection to Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome (AIDS), the most advanced stage of HIV disease, which is characterized by severe immune deficiency. The central mechanism by which HIV elevates cancer risk is through the chronic weakening of the body's immune defenses.<SEP>Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) or AIDS weakens the immune system, increasing the risk of squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is a condition that weakens the immune system, increasing the risk of CSCC.<SEP>Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is an infection that increases the risk of anal cancer by weakening the immune system.<SEP>Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection is a risk factor for anal cancer as it weakens the immune system.<SEP>Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is a virus for which testing may be recommended; having it leads to referral to a specialist but does not affect cancer treatment."}
