{"entity": "Clinical Stage (c)", "type": "method", "description": "Clinical Stage (c), often written as cTNM, is a rating system used to describe the extent of a cancer, such as breast cancer, before any treatment has been administered. It is determined through a combination of diagnostic methods, including a physical examination, biopsy, and imaging studies, along with other relevant tests. This pre-treatment assessment provides a standardized way to classify the cancer's severity and guide initial therapeutic decisions."}
{"entity": "Basal Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer. It is caused by damage to the DNA of basal cells, primarily from exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources. While it can occur in anyone, it is most frequently diagnosed in individuals with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, making fair skin a significant risk factor.

This cancer is characterized by its high treatability and curability, especially when detected and addressed early. A key clinical feature is that it rarely metastasizes, or spreads to other parts of the body. Accurate diagnostic testing is essential for confirming the diagnosis and for informing appropriate treatment planning.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a highly treatable and curable form of skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer, often treatable and curable when caught early.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can happen to anyone but is most common in people with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, with specific lesion appearances."}
{"entity": "Physical Exam", "type": "method", "description": "A physical exam is a fundamental, hands-on medical procedure conducted by a healthcare provider to assess a patient's overall health. It is a diagnostic method that involves checking vital signs, such as height, weight, and other metrics, and systematically examining the body for signs of disease or abnormality. The exam typically includes a physical assessment of body systems—such as the lungs, heart, and abdomen—and a functional assessment of the patient's physical abilities. Common components involve feeling and listening to organs, performing a complete head and neck exam, and palpating for abnormalities like enlarged lymph nodes.

The physical exam serves multiple critical purposes across various medical specialties. It is a core component of the general diagnostic process and routine medical care. In specialized fields, it is adapted for specific contexts: an anesthesiologist performs an exam of the throat and airway as part of a pre-anesthesia assessment; a hematologist/oncologist checks lymph nodes, the spleen, and the liver; and it is part of short-term follow-up care after procedures like a total thyroidectomy. In oncology, the physical exam is particularly vital. It helps determine the initial clinical stage of cancers, functions as a surveillance method to check for recurrence, and is essential for treatment planning and monitoring during active therapies like chemotherapy, often performed every 1 to 3 cycles. It also plays a key role in long-term surveillance during routine follow-up visits after treatment.

Ultimately, the information gathered from the physical exam, combined with the patient's medical history, provides crucial data on the patient's overall health status, physical ability, and treatment progress, making it a cornerstone of comprehensive patient management."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It frequently develops in sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head, neck, and the vermilion lip, and occurs more often in individuals with lighter skin tones.

The primary and preferred treatment for low-risk cases that have not spread is surgery. Other treatment options include radiation therapy, cryotherapy, and topical therapies. Cases are classified as local when the cancer has not spread to nearby lymph nodes or other sites.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that can be treated by various surgical methods, including curettage and electrodesiccation, PDEMA/Mohs surgery, and standard surgical excision.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is the specific type of squamous cell skin cancer discussed, for which testing and treatment are described."}
