{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It originates in the skin's squamous cells. CSCC occurs more frequently in individuals with lighter skin and is most commonly found on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head and neck. It can also form in scars or chronic wounds, a presentation that can be more difficult to treat.

In most cases, CSCC can be cured by the complete surgical removal of the tumor. For cases that are more advanced or difficult to treat, management strategies include targeted therapies, immunotherapy, and other forms of systemic therapy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which Mohs surgery is a recommended treatment option.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is a type of skin cancer with low-risk, high-risk, and very high-risk classifications, for which various surgical treatments are recommended."}
{"entity": "Blood Tests", "type": "method", "description": "Blood tests are medical diagnostic procedures involving the laboratory analysis of a blood sample, typically drawn from a vein. Their primary purposes are to assess a patient's general health, evaluate organ function (such as that of the liver and kidneys), check nutritional status, and detect signs of disease by measuring components like blood cells, proteins, hormones, and various chemicals. They are ordered when symptoms occur or a physical exam yields suspicious findings.

In oncology, blood tests are a fundamental part of the diagnostic, staging, treatment planning, and monitoring process for a wide array of cancers. This includes blood cancers like leukemias, lymphomas (such as cutaneous B-cell lymphoma and follicular lymphoma), and solid tumors including colon, pancreatic, breast, ovarian, liver, stomach, kidney, adrenal, bone, and rectal cancers. For specific cancers, tests may detect unique markers; for example, tests for suspected ovarian cancer often include a complete blood count (CBC), chemistry profile, liver function tests, and tumor marker tests. Blood tests provide crucial information about a patient's baseline health and organ function before cancer treatment begins.

Blood tests are seldom used alone for a definitive cancer diagnosis; their results are integrated with imaging studies and biopsies. They are ordered repeatedly to monitor a patient's response to therapies like chemotherapy, to check for cancer recurrence, and to optimize ongoing treatment. As key diagnostic reports, patients are often advised to obtain, organize, and include copies of their blood test results in a personal medical binder for comprehensive health management."}
