{"entity": "Diagnosis", "type": "concept", "description": "Diagnosis is the comprehensive medical process of identifying and naming a specific disease or condition, serving as the essential starting point for all subsequent treatment planning. It is a collaborative effort, typically involving a medical team that discusses findings with the patient, who is often advised to seek support during this period. The process generally begins after symptoms appear, as symptoms alone are frequently insufficient for a definitive identification.

The methodology is tailored to the suspected condition and employs a variety of tools, including physical examinations, blood tests, imaging studies, and surgical procedures such as biopsies. For solid tumors, like those in bladder, esophageal, liver, and kidney cancers, the process relies on a series of tests to confirm the disease's presence, location, and characteristics. Diagnosing a glioma or primary CNS lymphoma involves questions about symptom onset, physical exams, imaging, and often genetic testing or biopsy.

For hematologic cancers, diagnosis follows specific cellular criteria. Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML) is diagnosed based on the presence of a certain percentage of myeloid blasts in the bone marrow or blood, aided by molecular methods like RT-PCR. Similarly, Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL) requires that 20 percent or more of bone marrow cells are lymphoblasts. The process also applies to other conditions like squamous cell skin cancer. Following initial tests, results are discussed with the patient, and further testing may be required. Ongoing improvements in techniques, including biomarker testing and advanced imaging, aim to increase accuracy and shorten the time to diagnosis.<SEP>Diagnosis is the process of identifying a glioma or other brain tumor.<SEP>The process of identifying a disease, such as bone cancer, through methods like biopsy."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell skin cancer, also known as cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC), is the second most common type of skin cancer. It is highly treatable and often curable. This cancer typically begins as scaly patches on the skin and can develop from pre-cancerous lesions called actinic keratoses. It is most frequently caused by cumulative sun exposure over many years, with other major risk factors including indoor tanning and exposure to environmental toxins. It can also form within old wounds, burns, or scars.

Diagnosis is confirmed through a skin biopsy. The disease is classified as local, regional, or metastatic, with the potential to spread to nearby lymph nodes. Treatment depends on the cancer's extent and risk classification. Primary treatments are surgical, including Mohs surgery and standard excision, often with lymph node assessment. Other options include radiation therapy and topical treatments. For advanced cases, systemic therapies such as chemotherapy, EGFR inhibitors, and PD-1 inhibitors are used.

Given its risk of recurrence and the increased risk of developing other skin cancers, patients require specific follow-up monitoring schedules after treatment, particularly for local and regional forms of the disease.<SEP>Squamous cell skin cancer is a type of cancer that can be treated with systemic therapy, including PD-1 inhibitors.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which a weakened immune system is a risk factor, requiring regular screening and diagnosis via biopsy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer; recurrent tumors of this type are considered high-risk, and it can start in areas of damaged skin."}
{"entity": "Clinical Stage", "type": "concept", "description": "Clinical Stage, often denoted by a lowercase 'c' prefix (e.g., cN2, cM), is a standardized oncology system for describing the extent of a cancer before any treatment is administered. It represents a pre-treatment, best-estimate assessment of how far the cancer has spread from its original site. This stage is determined through a combination of diagnostic methods, including physical examination, biopsy results, and imaging tests such as CT scans or MRIs.

The primary purpose of assigning a clinical stage is to guide initial treatment planning and determine appropriate therapeutic options. It provides a crucial baseline for clinical decision-making prior to intervention. This application is illustrated in specific cancer types, such as serving as the pre-surgery estimate of a rectal cancer's extent or the pre-treatment assessment of how far ovarian cancer has spread.<SEP>The stage of nasopharyngeal cancer determined by imaging and biopsy results before any treatment.<SEP>Clinical stage (c) is the rating given before any treatment begins.<SEP>The clinical or pre-surgery stage is an estimate of cancer extent based on test results, used to determine treatment options.<SEP>Clinical stage (c) is assigned before any treatment, based on physical exam, biopsy, and imaging tests.<SEP>The clinical stage is a pre-treatment assessment that estimates how far cancer has spread, based on testing before surgery.<SEP>Clinical Stage is a type of prognostic stage determined before surgery."}
