{"entity": "Bone Marrow Tests", "type": "method", "description": "Bone Marrow Tests are diagnostic medical procedures that involve the extraction and analysis of samples of bone marrow, typically from the hip bone (pelvis). The two primary components of this testing are a bone marrow aspirate and a bone marrow biopsy. These tests are crucial for diagnosing, evaluating, and planning treatment for various hematologic cancers and blood disorders, and are a standard part of the diagnostic evaluation for investigating unexplained low blood cell counts and other marrow-related conditions.

Specifically, Bone Marrow Tests are essential for diagnosing Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL) by detecting the presence of lymphoblasts in the marrow and for examining the cells to confirm the disease. They are a key diagnostic tool for Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML), with the extracted samples being reviewed by an expert pathologist. For Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML), these tests are a standard part of the diagnostic assessment. In the case of Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL), bone marrow tests can be used for diagnosis or to investigate causes of low blood cell counts, though they are not frequently required for an initial CLL diagnosis.<SEP>Bone marrow tests are diagnostic procedures not often needed for Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL) diagnosis but may be done to investigate low blood cell counts.<SEP>Bone marrow tests are procedures specifically used to examine the bone marrow for blasts and genetic changes to diagnose AML.<SEP>Diagnostic procedures, including aspirate and biopsy, often performed on the hip bone to examine bone marrow."}
{"entity": "CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "CSCC, or Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma, is a form of squamous cell skin cancer. It is a type of skin cancer that can metastasize and is characterized by varying risk levels, including low-risk forms and very high-risk local disease. A specific risk factor is its potential to grow in previously radiated areas of the skin.

Treatment for CSCC is tailored based on its risk assessment. Surgical options are prominent, with Mohs micrographic surgery being a preferred treatment for very high-risk local tumors. Non-surgical treatments are also utilized, including radiation therapy (using electrons and photons), systemic therapies like the EGFR inhibitor Cetuximab, and PD-1 inhibitors. The choice of treatment, whether surgical or non-surgical, is recommended according to the cancer's risk level. A noted specific risk of treatment, particularly when the cancer is located near the eye, is the potential development of cataracts from radiation therapy.<SEP>CSCC is a type of cancer that can be treated with radiation therapy methods like EBRT and brachytherapy.<SEP>CSCC refers to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, a type of squamous cell skin cancer that may be treated with systemic therapy and radiation."}
