{"entity": "Physical Examination", "type": "method", "description": "A Physical Examination is a fundamental medical procedure that serves as a general health assessment. It is a key component of the initial diagnostic process for various conditions, including informing cancer treatment plans and specifically when Primary CNS Lymphoma is suspected. The examination typically involves a systematic approach where a healthcare provider listens to a patient's lungs and heart with a stethoscope, examines the eyes, ears, nose, and throat, and palpates (feels) the body to assess organ size, texture, and areas of tenderness or pain. This hands-on evaluation helps gather critical baseline information about a patient's overall health and identify potential physical signs of disease."}
{"entity": "Skin Exam", "type": "method", "description": "A skin exam is a specific type of physical examination performed by a doctor or healthcare provider that is focused entirely on the patient's skin. Its primary purpose is to identify concerning lesions. This procedure serves multiple diagnostic and monitoring roles. It is a standard follow-up method to check for the recurrence of skin cancers, such as squamous cell carcinoma and basal cell carcinoma, after treatment, and to screen for signs of new skin cancers.

