{"entity": "Tests", "type": "concept", "description": "Tests are a broad category of medical procedures and analyses used in the diagnosis, management, and monitoring of diseases, particularly cancer. Their primary functions include confirming a diagnosis, measuring the extent of disease, planning appropriate treatment, assessing the effectiveness of therapy, and monitoring for potential recurrence or late effects during follow-up care. The specific tests required vary significantly depending on the type of cancer. For instance, diagnosing and treating bladder cancer may involve blood tests, urine tests, cystoscopy, biopsy, and imaging. Diagnosing a glioma or leukemia, such as Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL) or Acute Lymphocytic Leukemia (ALL), each necessitates distinct diagnostic approaches, with ALL often involving specific blood and bone marrow tests. Similarly, tests are used to plan treatment for prostate cancer and to evaluate its effectiveness. These procedures are fundamental prerequisites for initiating treatment, as outlined in clinical guides, and encompass the assessments and general health tests individuals might receive throughout their care journey."}
{"entity": "Nonmelanoma Skin Cancers", "type": "concept", "description": "Nonmelanoma skin cancers, or keratinocyte carcinomas, refer to basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers that behave differently from melanoma.<SEP>Nonmelanoma skin cancers, or keratinocyte carcinomas, refer to basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers that behave differently from melanoma.<SEP>Nonmelanoma skin cancers, also called keratinocyte carcinomas, is a category that includes basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers because they do not behave like melanoma."}
{"entity": "Imaging Tests", "type": "method", "description": "Imaging tests are diagnostic medical procedures that create visual representations of the body's internal structures, including organs, tissues, and bones. Their primary purpose is to aid in the diagnosis, staging, and treatment planning of various diseases, with a major focus on cancer. These tests are fundamental in oncology for locating primary tumors, determining a tumor's size, shape, and precise location, and checking for the spread (metastasis) of cancer to other parts of the body. They are used to determine the clinical stage of cancer, monitor treatment response, detect disease progression or recurrence, and form a key component of post-treatment surveillance.

The applications of imaging tests span a wide spectrum of cancers. They are used to check lymph nodes for suspicious appearance indicating cancer spread and to detect conditions like swollen lymph nodes or an enlarged spleen in specific cancers such as Follicular Lymphoma. They are integral to the diagnostic process for cutaneous B-cell lymphoma and for visualizing internal structures in the testing for ovarian cancer. For prostate cancer, imaging is used to see if the disease has spread beyond the prostate, though it may not be needed for early-stage cases. Tumors of organs like the liver, kidney, and adrenal glands are often confirmed or discovered incidentally through these exams, sometimes performed for unrelated medical reasons.

Common imaging methods include CT scans, MRI, PET scans, ultrasound, bone scans, and mammograms. These tests are used alongside physical examinations, biopsies, and laboratory tests. The resulting images are interpreted by a diagnostic radiologist, who provides the detailed visual analysis necessary to detect abnormalities and guide all phases of clinical management."}
{"entity": "Regional CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "Regional CSCC, or regional cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, is an advanced form of squamous cell skin cancer characterized by its spread (metastasis) to nearby lymph nodes or tissues. This metastatic progression distinguishes it from localized disease and necessitates a more intensive management strategy.

The primary and recommended treatment for regional CSCC is surgical removal of the cancerous tissue from the lymph nodes. This is often followed by adjuvant therapy, a combined approach aimed at addressing any residual microscopic disease to improve outcomes. Due to its advanced and metastatic nature, regional CSCC requires more vigilant and frequent post-treatment monitoring compared to localized cancer. This monitoring typically involves regular follow-up physical examinations and imaging tests, such as CT scans, to detect any potential recurrence or further progression at the earliest possible stage."}
