{"entity": "Biopsy", "type": "method", "description": "A biopsy is a definitive medical diagnostic procedure involving the removal of a sample of cells, fluid, or tissue from the body for microscopic laboratory examination by a pathologist or hematopathologist. Its primary purpose is to confirm or rule out diseases, most commonly cancer, and to inform treatment planning, risk assessment, and staging. It is often performed when other tests, such as imaging or blood work, indicate a potential abnormality or yield unclear results.

The procedure is versatile and can be performed on virtually any tissue or organ. Specific applications include diagnosing conditions of the prostate, breast, lung, skin, lymph nodes, bone marrow, throat, cervix, thyroid, liver, and brain, as well as specific diseases like ovarian cancer, prostate cancer, brain tumors, bone cancer, primary CNS lymphoma, and various other lymphomas. Biopsies are frequently a required step to confirm a diagnosis before initiating treatments like chemotherapy, and they may be performed during initial surgery or before planned chemotherapy.

Common biopsy techniques include core needle biopsy, fine-needle aspiration, and surgical excision, and the procedure is often guided by imaging techniques such as ultrasound, CT scans, or MRI. As an invasive procedure, it typically requires local anesthetic and carries risks such as bleeding, infection, and potential scarring. In the specific case of a prostate biopsy, the procedure can temporarily increase PSA levels. The resulting pathological analysis is critical for providing an accurate diagnosis, determining the clinical stage of a condition, and frequently includes molecular biomarker testing to finalize an appropriate treatment plan.<SEP>The removal of a tissue sample from the body for diagnostic testing.<SEP>A biopsy is a procedure to remove cell or tissue samples to confirm a prostate cancer diagnosis."}
