{"entity": "Mohs Surgery", "type": "method", "description": "Mohs surgery is an advanced and precise surgical procedure primarily used to treat skin cancer, specifically cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC). It is performed by a specially trained dermatologic or Mohs surgeon. The technique involves the excision of a tumor layer by layer, with each removed layer being immediately examined under a microscope by the surgeon. This allows for real-time, microscopic checking of tissue margins to confirm whether all cancerous cells have been removed before the procedure is completed, thereby enabling immediate confirmation of complete cancer removal while preserving as much healthy surrounding tissue as possible.

Mohs surgery is classified as the most common form of PDEMA, a procedural category in dermatologic surgery. It is a recommended and frequently preferred surgical treatment for CSCC. Its applications are specified based on the risk level of the cancer. It is a recommended treatment option for local, low-risk CSCC. Furthermore, it is the preferred surgical option for high-risk and very high-risk localized CSCC, particularly in cases where the cancer has not spread to the lymph nodes. The procedure is also utilized in scenarios where cancer is found in the margin after an initial surgery. Following the complete removal of the tumor, reconstructive surgery is often performed to repair the surgical site."}
{"entity": "Basal Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer. It is caused by damage to the DNA of basal cells, primarily from exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources. While it can occur in anyone, it is most frequently diagnosed in individuals with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, making fair skin a significant risk factor.

This cancer is characterized by its high treatability and curability, especially when detected and addressed early. A key clinical feature is that it rarely metastasizes, or spreads to other parts of the body. Accurate diagnostic testing is essential for confirming the diagnosis and for informing appropriate treatment planning.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a highly treatable and curable form of skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer, often treatable and curable when caught early.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can happen to anyone but is most common in people with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, with specific lesion appearances."}
{"entity": "Curettage And Electrodesiccation Or Shave Excision", "type": "method", "description": "Curettage and electrodesiccation or shave excision are recommended treatment options for low-risk, local CSCC, often considered for early, small CSCC on the skin's surface."}
