{"entity": "Curettage And Electrodesiccation", "type": "method", "description": "Curettage and electrodesiccation (C&E) is a surgical method used for treating skin cancer, specifically cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC). It is a two-step procedure that involves first scraping off a tumor with a curette (curettage) and then cauterizing, or burning, the wound base with an electric needle (electrodesiccation).

This technique is a recommended treatment option for local, low-risk CSCC. It is typically considered suitable for early-stage, small tumors located on the surface of the skin. The procedure is valued for its effectiveness in managing these specific types of superficial skin cancers.<SEP>Curettage and electrodesiccation is a recommended surgical treatment for local, low-risk CSCC.<SEP>Curettage and electrodesiccation is a type of surgery used to treat squamous cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Surgery", "type": "event", "description": "Surgery is a conventional medical procedure involving operative manual and instrumental techniques to physically remove tissue, such as tumors or lesions. It serves as a primary treatment method for many cancers, fulfilling both therapeutic and diagnostic purposes. Therapeutically, it aims to completely remove cancer, slow its growth, or alleviate symptoms. Diagnostically, examining removed tissue provides a definitive diagnosis and determines the cancer's exact extent, type, and stage.

Surgery is a common and often main treatment for numerous specific cancers. These include basal and squamous cell skin cancers, thyroid cancer, early-stage cervical cancer, non-small cell lung cancer, rectal cancer, ovarian cancer, bladder cancer, gliomas, pancreatic cancer, and prostate cancer. It is also used for conditions like chondrosarcoma and chordoma, and is the preferred treatment for cancer that recurs in the neck if it can be removed based on size and location. For some cancers, such as ovarian cancer, testing is required to determine if surgery is possible, and it may not always be the first available option.

The procedure is frequently integrated into a multimodal treatment approach. A treatment team may assess it as a main goal, and it is often combined with systemic therapy, chemotherapy, or radiation given before or after. However, surgery is not suitable for all cases. Its feasibility depends on tumor characteristics, location, and patient health. It may not be suitable for some metastatic cancers and is normally not recommended for treating primary CNS lymphoma. Surgery carries inherent risks and common side effects including pain, swelling, and scars, and can lead to complications like vaginal stenosis. Patient factors such as smoking, vaping, overall health, and nutrition significantly impact wound healing and recovery.<SEP>Surgery is a primary treatment for ovarian cancer, often performed first by a gynecologic oncologist.<SEP>Surgery is a treatment method for cervical cancer, including procedures like hysterectomy and trachelectomy.<SEP>Surgery is the most common and effective treatment for most thyroid cancers, involving procedures like lobectomy or total thyroidectomy.<SEP>A procedure to remove tumor tissue for diagnosis and to determine the exact extent of cancer in the body.<SEP>Surgery is a medical procedure involving tissue removal, performed under general anesthesia, with a variable duration and recovery time."}
{"entity": "Cryotherapy", "type": "method", "description": "Cryotherapy is a medical treatment method that utilizes extreme cold, typically applied via a very cold liquid or tool such as liquid nitrogen, to freeze and destroy abnormal cells. Its primary application is in oncology and dermatology for targeting both precancerous and cancerous cells. Specifically, it is a common treatment option for conditions like actinic keratoses, which are identified as pre-cancerous skin lesions. The procedure works by applying the cold agent directly to the targeted tissue, causing the cells to be destroyed through the freezing process.<SEP>Cryotherapy, or cryosurgery, freezes and destroys precancerous and cancerous cells using a very cold substance like liquid nitrogen.<SEP>Cryotherapy is a treatment option for actinic keratoses, which are pre-cancerous lesions."}
{"entity": "Systemic Therapy", "type": "method", "description": "Systemic therapy is a broad category of cancer treatment that involves the administration of medicines, such as drugs or biological agents, which travel via the bloodstream to affect cells throughout the entire body. This distinguishes it from localized treatments like surgery or radiation. The primary types of systemic therapy include chemotherapy, targeted therapy, immunotherapy, and endocrine therapy. It is administered by a Medical Oncologist or oncology nurses, often intravenously.

Its applications are varied and depend on the specific cancer and its stage. Systemic therapy can be used as a primary treatment, administered before surgery (neoadjuvant) to shrink tumors, after surgery (adjuvant) to eliminate remaining cancer cells, in combination with radiation therapy, or when surgery is not possible. It is particularly crucial for metastatic, recurrent, or advanced disease, where it is a standard treatment.

Systemic therapy is used to treat a wide range of cancers, including but not limited to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, basal cell skin cancer, cervical cancer, bladder cancer, thyroid cancer, anal cancer, acute myeloid leukemia (AML), and acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL). For cancers like cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, it is typically reserved for cases where the disease has spread.

Because it affects cells throughout the body, systemic therapy impacts both cancerous and healthy cells, leading to potential side effects such as hair loss, fatigue, nausea, and low blood cell counts. For metastatic or advanced disease, its effectiveness is commonly monitored through medical imaging to assess the cancer's response.<SEP>Systemic therapy works throughout the body to treat cancer and includes chemotherapy, targeted therapy, and immunotherapy.<SEP>Systemic therapy refers to treatments like chemotherapy that affect the whole body, for which side effects must be managed.<SEP>Systemic Therapy is a treatment method for cancer that includes chemotherapy and immunotherapy, administered by a Medical Oncologist."}
{"entity": "PDEMA/Mohs Surgery", "type": "method", "description": "PDEMA/Mohs surgery is a type of surgery used for treating squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>PDEMA/Mohs surgery is a type of surgery used for treating squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>PDEMA/Mohs surgery is a type of surgery used to treat squamous cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Radiation Therapy", "type": "method", "description": "Radiation therapy is a standard medical treatment for cancer, prescribed and planned by a radiation oncologist. It uses high-energy radiation, such as x-rays or particles, to destroy cancer cells by damaging their DNA. The primary delivery methods are External Beam Radiation Therapy (EBRT) and brachytherapy (internal radiation). It is a local therapy, typically administered in multiple sessions over several weeks, with the goal of delivering a high dose to a tumor while limiting exposure to surrounding healthy tissue.

Its roles in cancer care are versatile. It can serve as a primary treatment, an adjuvant treatment after surgery to reduce recurrence risk, or a palliative treatment to alleviate symptoms. It is often utilized when surgery is not an option, when cancer remains after surgery, or if cancer recurs in a previously operated area. It is frequently combined with other therapies, such as concurrent chemotherapy (chemoradiation). Radiation therapy is a standard part of treatment for a wide spectrum of cancers, including but not limited to anal cancer, primary CNS lymphoma, thyroid cancer, squamous cell skin cancer, and cancers of the bladder, cervix, breast, head and neck, prostate, rectum, and lung. Specifically, it is a main treatment for primary CNS lymphoma and a listed treatment for thyroid cancer, particularly for cases that cannot be surgically removed, do not take up radioactive iodine, and are progressing.

A significant aspect involves managing side effects from damage to nearby healthy tissues. These include short-term effects like skin irritation and fatigue, and long-term risks such as organ damage. Specific risks include damage to reproductive organs causing infertility (noted in anal cancer treatment), vaginal stenosis from pelvic radiation, impacts on fertility, and the development of secondary cancers, especially if administered at a young age. Furthermore, if a squamous cell skin cancer later develops in an area that previously received radiation therapy, that cancer is considered high-risk. Radiation therapy also generally cannot be reused on the same area if cancer recurs."}
