{"entity": "Testing", "type": "method", "description": "Testing is a comprehensive medical diagnostic process used to identify, evaluate, and stage various diseases, particularly cancers, in order to formulate, adjust, and monitor treatment plans. It encompasses a wide array of procedures, including evaluations of medical history and symptoms, physical examinations, laboratory tests (such as blood tests), biopsies, and imaging studies. The primary objectives are to confirm a diagnosis, identify the specific types of cells or genetic abnormalities involved, determine how far a cancer has spread (staging), and assess its advancement.

This process is critically applied to numerous specific cancers. It is explicitly required for diagnosing and planning treatment for Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML), basal cell skin cancer, adrenal tumors, follicular lymphoma (Grade 3A), primary bone cancer, stomach cancer, gliomas, and prostate cancer. For specific conditions, testing may involve specialized techniques, such as skin exams for basal cell carcinoma, examination of surgically removed tissue and lymph nodes to determine cancer spread, or genetic tests that look for specific abnormalities in genes involved in DNA repair to help predict cancer behavior.

