{"entity": "Standard Surgical Excision", "type": "method", "description": "Standard surgical excision is a conventional surgical method for removing tissue, most commonly referenced in the context of treating cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC), a type of skin cancer. The procedure is performed in a medical office and involves the removal of a tumor along with a margin of surrounding normal tissue using a scalpel blade. The excised tissue is then sent for pathological examination to assess whether the margins are clear of cancer cells.

It is a recommended surgical treatment for both low-risk and high-risk local CSCC. For low-risk CSCC, it serves as a primary treatment option and is often performed if a tumor is found to be deeper than expected during an initial procedure. For high-risk or very high-risk local CSCC, the procedure is similarly recommended but involves the removal of a wider margin of normal tissue around the lesion. It is typically performed when specialized techniques like Mohs micrographic surgery or the PDEMA procedure are not available or possible, or if cancer remains after other treatments.

Following the excision, if pathological examination finds cancer cells at the margins of the removed tissue, further treatment is required. Depending on the size and nature of the surgical wound created, a reconstructive procedure such as a skin graft may be performed, either on the same day as the excision or a few days later.<SEP>Standard surgical excision is a recommended treatment option for low-risk, local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) and for high-risk or very high-risk CSCC that has not spread to lymph nodes."}
