{"entity": "CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "CSCC, or Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma, is a form of squamous cell skin cancer. It is a type of skin cancer that can metastasize and is characterized by varying risk levels, including low-risk forms and very high-risk local disease. A specific risk factor is its potential to grow in previously radiated areas of the skin.

Treatment for CSCC is tailored based on its risk assessment. Surgical options are prominent, with Mohs micrographic surgery being a preferred treatment for very high-risk local tumors. Non-surgical treatments are also utilized, including radiation therapy (using electrons and photons), systemic therapies like the EGFR inhibitor Cetuximab, and PD-1 inhibitors. The choice of treatment, whether surgical or non-surgical, is recommended according to the cancer's risk level. A noted specific risk of treatment, particularly when the cancer is located near the eye, is the potential development of cataracts from radiation therapy.<SEP>CSCC is a type of cancer that can be treated with radiation therapy methods like EBRT and brachytherapy.<SEP>CSCC refers to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, a type of squamous cell skin cancer that may be treated with systemic therapy and radiation."}
{"entity": "Basal Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer. It is caused by damage to the DNA of basal cells, primarily from exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources. While it can occur in anyone, it is most frequently diagnosed in individuals with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, making fair skin a significant risk factor.

This cancer is characterized by its high treatability and curability, especially when detected and addressed early. A key clinical feature is that it rarely metastasizes, or spreads to other parts of the body. Accurate diagnostic testing is essential for confirming the diagnosis and for informing appropriate treatment planning.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a highly treatable and curable form of skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer, often treatable and curable when caught early.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can happen to anyone but is most common in people with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, with specific lesion appearances."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It frequently develops in sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head, neck, and the vermilion lip, and occurs more often in individuals with lighter skin tones.

The primary and preferred treatment for low-risk cases that have not spread is surgery. Other treatment options include radiation therapy, cryotherapy, and topical therapies. Cases are classified as local when the cancer has not spread to nearby lymph nodes or other sites.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that can be treated by various surgical methods, including curettage and electrodesiccation, PDEMA/Mohs surgery, and standard surgical excision.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is the specific type of squamous cell skin cancer discussed, for which testing and treatment are described."}
{"entity": "Radiation Therapy Treatment", "type": "method", "description": "Radiation therapy is a treatment option that might be used for basal cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Radiation Therapy", "type": "method", "description": "Radiation therapy is a standard medical treatment for cancer, prescribed and planned by a radiation oncologist. It uses high-energy radiation, such as x-rays or particles, to destroy cancer cells by damaging their DNA. The primary delivery methods are External Beam Radiation Therapy (EBRT) and brachytherapy (internal radiation). It is a local therapy, typically administered in multiple sessions over several weeks, with the goal of delivering a high dose to a tumor while limiting exposure to surrounding healthy tissue.

Its roles in cancer care are versatile. It can serve as a primary treatment, an adjuvant treatment after surgery to reduce recurrence risk, or a palliative treatment to alleviate symptoms. It is often utilized when surgery is not an option, when cancer remains after surgery, or if cancer recurs in a previously operated area. It is frequently combined with other therapies, such as concurrent chemotherapy (chemoradiation). Radiation therapy is a standard part of treatment for a wide spectrum of cancers, including but not limited to anal cancer, primary CNS lymphoma, thyroid cancer, squamous cell skin cancer, and cancers of the bladder, cervix, breast, head and neck, prostate, rectum, and lung. Specifically, it is a main treatment for primary CNS lymphoma and a listed treatment for thyroid cancer, particularly for cases that cannot be surgically removed, do not take up radioactive iodine, and are progressing.

A significant aspect involves managing side effects from damage to nearby healthy tissues. These include short-term effects like skin irritation and fatigue, and long-term risks such as organ damage. Specific risks include damage to reproductive organs causing infertility (noted in anal cancer treatment), vaginal stenosis from pelvic radiation, impacts on fertility, and the development of secondary cancers, especially if administered at a young age. Furthermore, if a squamous cell skin cancer later develops in an area that previously received radiation therapy, that cancer is considered high-risk. Radiation therapy also generally cannot be reused on the same area if cancer recurs."}
{"entity": "Treatment", "type": "method", "description": "Treatment is a medical intervention or course of care provided to a patient to manage, cure, or address a disease, injury, or health condition. It is determined to be the best course of action based on a comprehensive assessment of the patient's medical history, diagnostic test results, and the specific characteristics of their condition. The primary goals are to manage disease, achieve remission, slow progression, reduce symptoms, and improve both the length and quality of a patient's life. Its details, including a specific start date, are recorded in the medical record and shared with the care team, and it is a phase during which having a support system is beneficial.

Treatment modalities are diverse and chosen through patient-doctor discussion, and they can be started when the care team deems it necessary. They include surgery, radiation therapy, and systemic therapies like chemotherapy or targeted therapy. The approach is highly specific and depends on the type of condition. For cancers, the assessment incorporates factors like stage, grade, and genetic mutations. For example, treatment for Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL) may involve pills or intravenous infusions, while active surveillance might be used for low-risk prostate cancer. For prostate cancer, treatment is a method used to slow down advanced disease, reduce symptoms, and help people live longer, though determining the best option is a key question. For Acute Lymphoblastic Leukemia (ALL), treatment depends on the type of ALL, age at diagnosis, and other factors. Managing gliomas presents particular challenges, though treatment options are improving.

Effectiveness is monitored through follow-up testing, with early detection generally leading to better outcomes. Individual response varies and can be influenced by overall health, nutrition, and lifestyle. Treatment can cause side effects and has implications for fertility, potentially necessitating preservation strategies, and some treatments must be avoided during pregnancy or breastfeeding. Ongoing medical advancements continue to improve treatment methods for various conditions.<SEP>Treatment refers to the medical interventions used for a disease, which can be affected by the type of blast phase cell.<SEP>The medical interventions for head and neck cancer, which can be affected by tobacco and alcohol use.<SEP>Medical intervention that should not be delayed by a lumbar puncture procedure.<SEP>Treatment is an intervention applied to a disease, which is more effective when the disease is found early through screening."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell skin cancer, also known as cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC), is the second most common type of skin cancer. It is highly treatable and often curable. This cancer typically begins as scaly patches on the skin and can develop from pre-cancerous lesions called actinic keratoses. It is most frequently caused by cumulative sun exposure over many years, with other major risk factors including indoor tanning and exposure to environmental toxins. It can also form within old wounds, burns, or scars.

Diagnosis is confirmed through a skin biopsy. The disease is classified as local, regional, or metastatic, with the potential to spread to nearby lymph nodes. Treatment depends on the cancer's extent and risk classification. Primary treatments are surgical, including Mohs surgery and standard excision, often with lymph node assessment. Other options include radiation therapy and topical treatments. For advanced cases, systemic therapies such as chemotherapy, EGFR inhibitors, and PD-1 inhibitors are used.

Given its risk of recurrence and the increased risk of developing other skin cancers, patients require specific follow-up monitoring schedules after treatment, particularly for local and regional forms of the disease.<SEP>Squamous cell skin cancer is a type of cancer that can be treated with systemic therapy, including PD-1 inhibitors.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which a weakened immune system is a risk factor, requiring regular screening and diagnosis via biopsy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer; recurrent tumors of this type are considered high-risk, and it can start in areas of damaged skin."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Skin Cancer (CSCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer for which several treatments are described.<SEP>Squamous Cell Skin Cancer is a type of cancer that can be regional (spread to lymph nodes) or metastatic."}
{"entity": "Systemic Therapy", "type": "method", "description": "Systemic therapy is a broad category of cancer treatment that involves the administration of medicines, such as drugs or biological agents, which travel via the bloodstream to affect cells throughout the entire body. This distinguishes it from localized treatments like surgery or radiation. The primary types of systemic therapy include chemotherapy, targeted therapy, immunotherapy, and endocrine therapy. It is administered by a Medical Oncologist or oncology nurses, often intravenously.

Its applications are varied and depend on the specific cancer and its stage. Systemic therapy can be used as a primary treatment, administered before surgery (neoadjuvant) to shrink tumors, after surgery (adjuvant) to eliminate remaining cancer cells, in combination with radiation therapy, or when surgery is not possible. It is particularly crucial for metastatic, recurrent, or advanced disease, where it is a standard treatment.

Systemic therapy is used to treat a wide range of cancers, including but not limited to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, basal cell skin cancer, cervical cancer, bladder cancer, thyroid cancer, anal cancer, acute myeloid leukemia (AML), and acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL). For cancers like cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, it is typically reserved for cases where the disease has spread.

Because it affects cells throughout the body, systemic therapy impacts both cancerous and healthy cells, leading to potential side effects such as hair loss, fatigue, nausea, and low blood cell counts. For metastatic or advanced disease, its effectiveness is commonly monitored through medical imaging to assess the cancer's response.<SEP>Systemic therapy works throughout the body to treat cancer and includes chemotherapy, targeted therapy, and immunotherapy.<SEP>Systemic therapy refers to treatments like chemotherapy that affect the whole body, for which side effects must be managed.<SEP>Systemic Therapy is a treatment method for cancer that includes chemotherapy and immunotherapy, administered by a Medical Oncologist."}
{"entity": "Local Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is usually treated with surgery.<SEP>Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is usually treated with surgery.<SEP>Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It originates in the skin's squamous cells. CSCC occurs more frequently in individuals with lighter skin and is most commonly found on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head and neck. It can also form in scars or chronic wounds, a presentation that can be more difficult to treat.

In most cases, CSCC can be cured by the complete surgical removal of the tumor. For cases that are more advanced or difficult to treat, management strategies include targeted therapies, immunotherapy, and other forms of systemic therapy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which Mohs surgery is a recommended treatment option.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is a type of skin cancer with low-risk, high-risk, and very high-risk classifications, for which various surgical treatments are recommended."}
{"entity": "Basal Cell Nevus Syndrome", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell nevus syndrome is a genetic condition that increases the risk of radiation-induced skin cancer, making radiation therapy unsuitable.<SEP>A genetic condition that increases the risk of radiation-induced skin cancer.<SEP>A genetic condition that increases the risk of radiation-induced skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Local CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "Local CSCC, which stands for Local Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (also commonly referred to as squamous cell skin cancer), is a form of skin cancer that is confined to its original site. It is specifically defined by the absence of spread, or metastasis, to nearby lymph nodes. In some descriptions, this local confinement is further clarified as cancer that has not spread beyond the original site.

The primary and most common treatment for Local CSCC is surgical removal. Following treatment, this diagnosis necessitates adherence to specific, structured follow-up monitoring schedules. The frequency and nature of these required monitoring exams are directly influenced by the local, non-metastatic status of the cancer.<SEP>Local CSCC is a type of squamous cell skin cancer that is confined to its original site and may be monitored with imaging tests.<SEP>Local CSCC is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is most often treated with surgery."}
{"entity": "Surgery", "type": "event", "description": "Surgery is a conventional medical procedure involving operative manual and instrumental techniques to physically remove tissue, such as tumors or lesions. It serves as a primary treatment method for many cancers, fulfilling both therapeutic and diagnostic purposes. Therapeutically, it aims to completely remove cancer, slow its growth, or alleviate symptoms. Diagnostically, examining removed tissue provides a definitive diagnosis and determines the cancer's exact extent, type, and stage.

Surgery is a common and often main treatment for numerous specific cancers. These include basal and squamous cell skin cancers, thyroid cancer, early-stage cervical cancer, non-small cell lung cancer, rectal cancer, ovarian cancer, bladder cancer, gliomas, pancreatic cancer, and prostate cancer. It is also used for conditions like chondrosarcoma and chordoma, and is the preferred treatment for cancer that recurs in the neck if it can be removed based on size and location. For some cancers, such as ovarian cancer, testing is required to determine if surgery is possible, and it may not always be the first available option.

The procedure is frequently integrated into a multimodal treatment approach. A treatment team may assess it as a main goal, and it is often combined with systemic therapy, chemotherapy, or radiation given before or after. However, surgery is not suitable for all cases. Its feasibility depends on tumor characteristics, location, and patient health. It may not be suitable for some metastatic cancers and is normally not recommended for treating primary CNS lymphoma. Surgery carries inherent risks and common side effects including pain, swelling, and scars, and can lead to complications like vaginal stenosis. Patient factors such as smoking, vaping, overall health, and nutrition significantly impact wound healing and recovery.<SEP>Surgery is a primary treatment for ovarian cancer, often performed first by a gynecologic oncologist.<SEP>Surgery is a treatment method for cervical cancer, including procedures like hysterectomy and trachelectomy.<SEP>Surgery is the most common and effective treatment for most thyroid cancers, involving procedures like lobectomy or total thyroidectomy.<SEP>A procedure to remove tumor tissue for diagnosis and to determine the exact extent of cancer in the body.<SEP>Surgery is a medical procedure involving tissue removal, performed under general anesthesia, with a variable duration and recovery time."}
