{"entity": "Cancer Cells", "type": "concept", "description": "Cancer cells are abnormal, malignant cells that arise from genetic mutations, which disrupt normal cellular instructions and allow them to break the rules governing healthy tissue. Their hallmark behaviors include uncontrollable multiplication, evasion of programmed cell death (apoptosis), and the ability to crowd out and damage normal cells, leading to symptoms and the formation of primary tumors. A key danger is their capacity for invasion and metastasis; they can break away from the primary tumor, invade surrounding tissues, and travel through the bloodstream or lymphatic system to establish secondary tumors in distant organs. This potential for spread, particularly through the lymphatic system, often prompts procedures like lymph node dissection during surgery for diagnostic and therapeutic purposes.

These cells exhibit distinct biological, metabolic, and physical properties. They are characterized by specific DNA mutations, altered protein expression, and other biomarkers, which pathologists study by analyzing tumor samples, biopsies, lymph nodes, and tissue margins. This laboratory analysis is critical for diagnosing specific cancers (such as glioma), determining the cancer grade by comparison to normal cells, and assessing risk. A defining metabolic trait is their accelerated rate of glucose consumption, which fuels their rapid division. This high metabolic activity is exploited in medical imaging; during a Positron Emission Tomography (PET) scan, cancer cells take up a radioactive sugar tracer and often appear as bright spots due to their faster sugar use, though not all such bright spots are cancerous.

Consequently, cancer cells are the fundamental target of all cancer therapies. Their confirmed presence in a tumor or surrounding tissue after surgery typically necessitates further treatment. Therapies—including surgery, radiation, chemotherapy, targeted therapy, and immunotherapy—aim to destroy these abnormal cells or control their growth, with diagnosis and treatment strategies heavily reliant on their analysis.<SEP>Cancer cells are the target of radiation therapy, which uses high-energy x-rays to kill them.<SEP>Abnormal cells that can appear as bright spots on a PET scan, though not all tumors are detectable by this method.<SEP>Abnormal cells that may be found in the spinal fluid and can indicate the spread of cancer.<SEP>Cancer cells are abnormal cells that are tested for in samples taken from fluid or peritoneal washings."}
