{"entity": "Basal Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, more common than squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, more common than squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, mentioned as a point of comparison for squamous cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Recurrence", "type": "concept", "description": "Recurrence, in the context of oncology, is the return of cancer after a period of being cancer-free following initial treatment, an event also commonly referred to as a relapse. It is a potential outcome that doctors assess based on specific cancer features and patient risk factors. The nature and location of a recurrence vary significantly by cancer type. It can manifest as a local return at the original site, a regional return in nearby areas, or a distant metastasis to lymph nodes or other body parts. For example, basal cell skin cancer may return locally or metastasize, thyroid cancer can recur in the neck or distant areas, and many cancers can spread to distant organs.

Detection relies on surveillance methods during the post-treatment period, with imaging such as MRI being a common tool. Specific techniques like PSMA/PET imaging are employed for monitoring cancers like prostate cancer. A recurrence may also be indicated by the emergence of specific symptoms. The clinical management of recurrence is a critical element in cancer care, directly impacting prognosis and subsequent treatment decisions. Treatment is highly dependent on the location and type of the recurrent cancer and may include strategies like targeted therapy and immunotherapy for cervical cancer, adjuvant intravesical BCG for bladder cancer to lower the risk, or distinct considerations in rectal cancer management. This concept is a key topic across numerous specific cancer types, including prostate, ovarian, cervical, thyroid, and skin cancers.<SEP>Recurrence refers to anal cancer that returns after initial treatment, potentially requiring surgery.<SEP>Recurrence refers to ovarian cancer that returns after initial treatment."}
{"entity": "Basal Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer. It is caused by damage to the DNA of basal cells, primarily from exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources. While it can occur in anyone, it is most frequently diagnosed in individuals with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, making fair skin a significant risk factor.

This cancer is characterized by its high treatability and curability, especially when detected and addressed early. A key clinical feature is that it rarely metastasizes, or spreads to other parts of the body. Accurate diagnostic testing is essential for confirming the diagnosis and for informing appropriate treatment planning.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a highly treatable and curable form of skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer, often treatable and curable when caught early.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can happen to anyone but is most common in people with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, with specific lesion appearances."}
{"entity": "Recurrent Ovarian Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Recurrent ovarian cancer is a condition in which ovarian cancer returns after the completion of initial treatment. This recurrence necessitates specific management strategies distinct from those used for the initial diagnosis. A cornerstone of guiding subsequent therapy for recurrent ovarian cancer is biomarker testing, which is generally recommended to inform treatment decisions."}
{"entity": "IBC", "type": "concept", "description": "IBC is a type of breast cancer that can be difficult to diagnose, often presenting without a lump but with swelling and redness."}
{"entity": "Surveillance", "type": "method", "description": "Surveillance, in the context of cancer care, is the comprehensive and ongoing process of follow-up monitoring conducted after a patient has completed initial treatment and entered remission. Its primary purpose is to detect any possible recurrence of cancer at the earliest, most treatable stage, thereby improving long-term health outcomes. This strategy is a standard phase of post-treatment management across various cancer types, specifically mentioned for anal, ovarian, cervical, and non-metastatic colon cancers.

The process involves a scheduled plan of regular follow-up care, which includes physical examinations and specific tests. Common components are digital rectal exams (DRE), lymph node examinations, proctoscopies or anoscopies, and various forms of medical imaging. The frequency of these checks is typically highest in the first few years. For anal cancer, a specific regimen may include DRE and lymph node exams every 3 to 6 months for 5 years and anoscopy every 6 to 12 months for 3 years.

Ultimately, surveillance is a critical management strategy designed to find new cancer growth or recurrence early. It is initiated after treatment when a patient is in complete remission and shows no signs of the disease. Its findings directly influence subsequent treatment decisions if a recurrence is detected.<SEP>Surveillance is a phase of care following treatment for ovarian cancer."}
