{"entity": "SCC", "type": "concept", "description": "SCC is the focus of the book, referring to a type of cancer that forms in the thin, flat cells of the mucus membranes of the nasopharynx.<SEP>SCC is an abbreviation for Squamous Cell Carcinoma, the most common type of nasopharyngeal cancer."}
{"entity": "Ovarian Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Ovarian cancer is a type of cancer that originates in the ovaries, most commonly beginning in the epithelium (the surface layer of tissue) or other ovarian tissues, though it can also start in the fallopian tubes. It is clinically related to primary peritoneal cancer and fallopian tube cancer. Symptoms are often non-specific and may not appear until the tumor is large or the cancer has spread, which can affect a patient's nutrition.

Its diagnosis and management are closely linked to hereditary genetic syndromes. Inherited germline mutations in genes like BRCA1, BRCA2, and those associated with Lynch syndrome significantly increase risk, and a family history of the disease is also a key risk factor. Consequently, genetic testing and tumor testing for BRCA and other DNA repair gene mutations are now recommended for every diagnosis.

The disease is diagnosed and evaluated through various medical procedures. Diagnostic methods include imaging studies such as ultrasound, CT scans, MRI, PET scans, and chest x-rays. Definitive tissue diagnosis is achieved via procedures like laparoscopy and biopsy. Tumor markers, most notably CA-125, are utilized for both diagnosis and monitoring. The progression is staged using the FIGO system (Stages I through IV with substages), which directly impacts patient outcomes.

Treatment typically involves a combination of surgery and chemotherapy. Surgical methods include laparotomy, laparoscopy, hysterectomy, bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy (BSO), and surgical staging. Platinum-based chemotherapy, such as specific regimens involving paclitaxel with carboplatin, is a standard recommendation. Following initial treatment, maintenance therapy options include PARP inhibitors and the targeted drug bevacizumab. The most common histological types are High-Grade Serous Carcinoma and High-Grade Endometrioid Carcinoma.<SEP>Ovarian cancer is a disease that can be recurrent and is diagnosed through biopsy and biomarker testing.<SEP>The primary disease discussed, which includes various epithelial and non-epithelial types and requires diagnosis and treatment by a specialized team."}
{"entity": "Non-Clear Cell RCC", "type": "concept", "description": "Non-Clear Cell Renal Cell Carcinoma (nccRCC) is a broad category of renal cell carcinoma (RCC) subtypes that are defined by not being the clear cell RCC subtype. It is, therefore, a collective term for several distinct subtypes of kidney cancer.

The category encompasses multiple specific histological subtypes. The most common among these is papillary RCC. Another major subtype included within non-clear cell RCC is chromophobe RCC. Overall, non-clear cell RCC represents a significant grouping of RCC variants that are pathologically and clinically distinct from the more prevalent clear cell RCC."}
{"entity": "ELOC (formerly TCEB1)-Mutated RCC", "type": "concept", "description": "ELOC (formerly TCEB1)-Mutated RCC is a recently defined type of renal cell carcinoma."}
{"entity": "Thyroid Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Thyroid cancer is a disease in which malignant cells form in the tissues of the thyroid gland, often beginning as nodules. It is notably the most common cancer in adults aged 18 to 33 years. Risk factors include radiation exposure and a family history of the disease.

There are several distinct types, including papillary, follicular, medullary, and the particularly aggressive anaplastic thyroid cancer. Most types are highly curable with appropriate treatment, though the disease's characteristics—such as its extent, invasiveness, and potential to spread—significantly influence management and prognosis. It is a condition that can recur after treatment, necessitating long-term monitoring.

Surgery is the primary treatment for most cases, with active surveillance considered for very-low-risk tumors. Additional therapies are employed based on the specific type and stage. These include radioactive iodine (RAI) therapy, a targeted treatment particularly effective for differentiated thyroid cancers that take up iodine, but not for medullary or anaplastic types. Other options are external beam radiation therapy, hormone therapy, systemic therapies like chemotherapy and targeted drugs, and enrollment in clinical trials. Detection can involve whole-body scans. Treatment is typically overseen by a multidisciplinary team.<SEP>Thyroid cancer is a disease treated by various methods, with surgery being the most common treatment."}
