{"entity": "Survivorship", "type": "concept", "description": "Survivorship is a distinct phase of care that begins after the completion of primary cancer treatment. Its primary purpose is to address the unique and ongoing needs of individuals who have survived cancer. This phase centrally involves medical surveillance, including regular follow-up care, specific testing to monitor for cancer recurrence, and the management of long-term and late side effects of the treatment itself.

Beyond this clinical surveillance, survivorship comprehensively encompasses a broader range of care essential to a survivor's well-being. This includes managing the physical, emotional, and psychosocial consequences of cancer and its treatment, as well as financial issues that may arise. Furthermore, survivorship care focuses on promoting healthy habits and addressing all aspects of life affected by the cancer experience. Therefore, survivorship is defined not merely by the absence of disease but by the holistic support required for a patient's long-term health and quality of life after treatment.<SEP>The phase of care and life after completing primary cancer treatment, focusing on health and well-being.<SEP>The phase of care following cancer treatment, encompassing surveillance and overall well-being.<SEP>Survivorship focuses on the physical, emotional, and financial issues unique to cancer survivors, including managing side effects and maintaining health.<SEP>A phase of care important for cancer survivors, involving surveillance testing and keeping alert for symptoms of cancer recurrence.<SEP>The phase of care focusing on managing long-term side effects and maintaining health after cancer treatment."}
{"entity": "Cancer Center", "type": "organization", "description": "A Cancer Center is a specialized medical facility, such as a dedicated hospital or a distinct unit within a larger hospital, that focuses on the comprehensive diagnosis and treatment of cancer. Its core functions include performing diagnostic procedures like PET/CT scans and administering a wide array of treatments for various cancer types. Patient care is delivered by specialized, multidisciplinary teams, which include experienced surgeons who perform essential procedures such as biopsies.

These centers are particularly recommended for their specific expertise in managing complex and particular cancers and subtypes. This includes, but is not limited to, anal cancer, acute myeloid leukemia (AML), follicular lymphoma (FL), diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL), and gray zone lymphomas. This deep expertise is crucial for making complex treatment decisions, such as determining whether to treat Grade 3A FL as classic FL or as the more aggressive DLBCL.

