{"entity": "Symptoms", "type": "concept", "description": "Symptoms are the subjective physical or mental indications of a disease, disorder, or medical condition that a patient experiences and reports to their healthcare team. As patient-reported issues, they are crucial for aiding in diagnosis and treatment planning, though they are often insufficient alone to identify a specific illness. The consistent guidance for all patients is to communicate any and all symptoms they experience to their care providers.

Symptoms can manifest in diverse ways depending on the underlying condition. They may include general physical manifestations such as pain, bloating, weight loss, fatigue, heartburn, and trouble eating. More specific examples related to prostate issues include urinary changes (like frequent urination), sexual dysfunction, blood in urine or semen, and pelvic or bone pain. Neurological symptoms from brain conditions can include headaches, seizures, and personality changes. Symptoms may also arise from hormonal imbalances or from the physical damage caused by conditions like cancer, where abnormal cells crowd out normal tissue.

Notably, some conditions, like early-stage prostate cancer or cancers targeted by screening programs, may show no symptoms for a long time. This emphasizes that screening aims to detect disease before symptoms appear. Regardless of this variability, reporting all symptoms remains a fundamental part of patient care.<SEP>Symptoms are signs of illness that occur when a brain tumor affects a specific area of the brain, related to the tumor's location and size."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) is a type of cancer that originates from squamous cells, which are thin, flat cells. It is notably the most common type of cancer found in two distinct anatomical locations. First, it is the most common type of mouth cancer, specifically forming in the squamous cells that line the mucous membranes of the oral cavity. Second, it is also the most common type of nasopharyngeal cancer, which affects the nasopharynx, the upper part of the throat behind the nose.<SEP>Squamous cell carcinoma is the most common type of mouth cancer, forming in the thin, flat cells of the mouth's mucous membranes."}
