{"entity": "Basal Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, more common than squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, more common than squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, mentioned as a point of comparison for squamous cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Follow-Up Care", "type": "concept", "description": "Follow-up care is the ongoing medical care, monitoring, and surveillance required after a patient has undergone treatment for a serious condition, most commonly cancer. Its primary purposes are to monitor a patient's overall health, manage any long-term side effects of treatment, and check for signs of disease recurrence. This care typically involves regular medical check-ups and specific tests.

A core component of follow-up care is the structured testing and surveillance implemented after surgical procedures. The specific plan varies significantly depending on the type of surgery performed; for instance, the follow-up protocol differs between a lobectomy and a total thyroidectomy. More broadly, this care involves careful planning and specific types of monitoring for various conditions, such as the surveillance of lung nodules."}
{"entity": "Basal Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer. It is caused by damage to the DNA of basal cells, primarily from exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources. While it can occur in anyone, it is most frequently diagnosed in individuals with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, making fair skin a significant risk factor.

This cancer is characterized by its high treatability and curability, especially when detected and addressed early. A key clinical feature is that it rarely metastasizes, or spreads to other parts of the body. Accurate diagnostic testing is essential for confirming the diagnosis and for informing appropriate treatment planning.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a highly treatable and curable form of skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer, often treatable and curable when caught early.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can happen to anyone but is most common in people with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, with specific lesion appearances."}
{"entity": "Tests", "type": "concept", "description": "Tests are a broad category of medical procedures and analyses used in the diagnosis, management, and monitoring of diseases, particularly cancer. Their primary functions include confirming a diagnosis, measuring the extent of disease, planning appropriate treatment, assessing the effectiveness of therapy, and monitoring for potential recurrence or late effects during follow-up care. The specific tests required vary significantly depending on the type of cancer. For instance, diagnosing and treating bladder cancer may involve blood tests, urine tests, cystoscopy, biopsy, and imaging. Diagnosing a glioma or leukemia, such as Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL) or Acute Lymphocytic Leukemia (ALL), each necessitates distinct diagnostic approaches, with ALL often involving specific blood and bone marrow tests. Similarly, tests are used to plan treatment for prostate cancer and to evaluate its effectiveness. These procedures are fundamental prerequisites for initiating treatment, as outlined in clinical guides, and encompass the assessments and general health tests individuals might receive throughout their care journey."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It originates in the skin's squamous cells. CSCC occurs more frequently in individuals with lighter skin and is most commonly found on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head and neck. It can also form in scars or chronic wounds, a presentation that can be more difficult to treat.

In most cases, CSCC can be cured by the complete surgical removal of the tumor. For cases that are more advanced or difficult to treat, management strategies include targeted therapies, immunotherapy, and other forms of systemic therapy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which Mohs surgery is a recommended treatment option.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is a type of skin cancer with low-risk, high-risk, and very high-risk classifications, for which various surgical treatments are recommended."}
{"entity": "Doctor", "type": "person", "description": "A doctor is a medical professional and central member of a patient's healthcare team responsible for comprehensive care. Their primary role involves direct patient interaction, beginning with consultations where they review information, take health histories, discuss symptoms, and perform physical examinations. To diagnose conditions, a doctor orders and interprets diagnostic tests, such as reviewing pathology reports, and performs procedures like biopsies, curettage, or selecting the appropriate skin biopsy method based on a lesion's characteristics. They also assess a patient's blood cell levels to determine the body's ability to carry oxygen, fight infection, and control bleeding.

Following assessment, the doctor engages in shared decision-making, explaining results and discussing treatment options, risks, and personalized recommendations. Treatment may involve surgery, chemotherapy, radiation, or targeted therapy. The doctor monitors effectiveness, manages side effects, and for recurrent disease, may suggest steps like secondary surgery or additional biomarker testing. They coordinate long-term management and follow-up care to monitor recurrence risk. A doctor also advises patients on whether a clinical trial may be a suitable treatment option.

A doctor's responsibilities extend to preventive care and holistic health guidance. This includes advising on lifestyle factors like smoking cessation, exercise, and bone health, and providing counseling and medications to quit smoking. They address sexual health, discuss fertility-related risks and preservation options, and provide recommendations on pregnancy planning after treatment. Doctors also provide guidance on birth control options, such as IUDs and barrier methods, and recommend appropriate screenings and genetic testing when indicated. They may advise patients on pre-test preparations, such as avoiding certain activities before a PSA test, and refer patients to specialists to ensure a coordinated continuum of care.<SEP>A healthcare provider who may perform specialized exams like a mirror or fiberoptic scope examination.<SEP>The doctor is a medical professional who may perform a peritoneal washing or provide surgical instructions.<SEP>A doctor is a medical professional a patient can talk to about germline testing or a referral to a genetic counselor."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It frequently develops in sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head, neck, and the vermilion lip, and occurs more often in individuals with lighter skin tones.

The primary and preferred treatment for low-risk cases that have not spread is surgery. Other treatment options include radiation therapy, cryotherapy, and topical therapies. Cases are classified as local when the cancer has not spread to nearby lymph nodes or other sites.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that can be treated by various surgical methods, including curettage and electrodesiccation, PDEMA/Mohs surgery, and standard surgical excision.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is the specific type of squamous cell skin cancer discussed, for which testing and treatment are described."}
{"entity": "Patient", "type": "person", "description": "A patient is an individual receiving medical care, diagnosis, or treatment, serving as the central and active participant within a healthcare team. This role is emphasized across all medical contexts, from general health management to specific conditions like various cancers, including chronic myeloid leukemia (CML), acute myeloid leukemia (AML), acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL), chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), prostate cancer, thyroid cancer, bone cancer, breast cancer, ovarian cancer, and bladder cancer. A patient can be of any age.

The patient's journey encompasses the entire care continuum, from initial diagnostic testing—such as physical exams, imaging, scans, biopsies, or HIV testing—through treatment planning and delivery, and into survivorship. Their specific condition, symptoms, overall health, and the characteristics of their disease are fundamental considerations for the medical team. This includes factors like potential allergies or kidney issues that may affect the use of contrast agents during imaging tests. The team discusses diagnosis and treatment options with the patient, which may include systemic therapy, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, surgery, or participation in clinical trials.

Key patient responsibilities emphasize active participation and collaboration. Patients are encouraged to communicate effectively by reporting symptoms, providing a full health history, disclosing all medications, and communicating any relevant conditions. They engage in shared decision-making to create a care plan based on personal goals, preferences, and quality of life, which involves asking questions about treatment options, processes, side effects, and potential outcomes. Patients are also advised to be organized and proactive by managing health information, taking notes, organizing documents, seeking second opinions, bringing a companion to appointments, and seeking support. This collaborative approach extends to managing health through medical advice regarding exercise, diet, medication, and lifestyle changes, including following specific at-home care instructions during treatments.<SEP>The Patient is the individual undergoing cancer treatment, advised to discuss fertility and pregnancy with their care team.<SEP>The patient is the individual receiving cancer treatment, who discusses preferences with their care team and may receive a catheter or port.<SEP>The patient is the individual undergoing medical imaging procedures such as MRI and CT scans, who may need to hold their breath or discuss claustrophobia.<SEP>The individual undergoing medical procedures such as a stereotactic biopsy and MRI scan for primary CNS lymphoma.<SEP>The individual undergoing medical examinations and treatment for head and neck cancer."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell skin cancer, also known as cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC), is the second most common type of skin cancer. It is highly treatable and often curable. This cancer typically begins as scaly patches on the skin and can develop from pre-cancerous lesions called actinic keratoses. It is most frequently caused by cumulative sun exposure over many years, with other major risk factors including indoor tanning and exposure to environmental toxins. It can also form within old wounds, burns, or scars.

Diagnosis is confirmed through a skin biopsy. The disease is classified as local, regional, or metastatic, with the potential to spread to nearby lymph nodes. Treatment depends on the cancer's extent and risk classification. Primary treatments are surgical, including Mohs surgery and standard excision, often with lymph node assessment. Other options include radiation therapy and topical treatments. For advanced cases, systemic therapies such as chemotherapy, EGFR inhibitors, and PD-1 inhibitors are used.

Given its risk of recurrence and the increased risk of developing other skin cancers, patients require specific follow-up monitoring schedules after treatment, particularly for local and regional forms of the disease.<SEP>Squamous cell skin cancer is a type of cancer that can be treated with systemic therapy, including PD-1 inhibitors.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which a weakened immune system is a risk factor, requiring regular screening and diagnosis via biopsy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer; recurrent tumors of this type are considered high-risk, and it can start in areas of damaged skin."}
{"entity": "Blood Tests", "type": "method", "description": "Blood tests are medical diagnostic procedures involving the laboratory analysis of a blood sample, typically drawn from a vein. Their primary purposes are to assess a patient's general health, evaluate organ function (such as that of the liver and kidneys), check nutritional status, and detect signs of disease by measuring components like blood cells, proteins, hormones, and various chemicals. They are ordered when symptoms occur or a physical exam yields suspicious findings.

In oncology, blood tests are a fundamental part of the diagnostic, staging, treatment planning, and monitoring process for a wide array of cancers. This includes blood cancers like leukemias, lymphomas (such as cutaneous B-cell lymphoma and follicular lymphoma), and solid tumors including colon, pancreatic, breast, ovarian, liver, stomach, kidney, adrenal, bone, and rectal cancers. For specific cancers, tests may detect unique markers; for example, tests for suspected ovarian cancer often include a complete blood count (CBC), chemistry profile, liver function tests, and tumor marker tests. Blood tests provide crucial information about a patient's baseline health and organ function before cancer treatment begins.

Blood tests are seldom used alone for a definitive cancer diagnosis; their results are integrated with imaging studies and biopsies. They are ordered repeatedly to monitor a patient's response to therapies like chemotherapy, to check for cancer recurrence, and to optimize ongoing treatment. As key diagnostic reports, patients are often advised to obtain, organize, and include copies of their blood test results in a personal medical binder for comprehensive health management."}
