{"entity": "MRI", "type": "method", "description": "Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) is a major diagnostic medical imaging technique that uses powerful magnetic fields and radio waves, rather than ionizing radiation, to produce highly detailed pictures of the body's interior. The procedure requires the patient to lie motionless within a large, confined machine for a scan typically lasting 30 to 60 minutes, and all metal objects must be removed due to the strong magnetic field. To enhance image clarity, a contrast material is often administered intravenously, and scans are frequently performed both with and without this agent. In specific examinations, such as for abdominal or rectal cancers, a rectal gel or coil device may also be used.

MRI is a versatile and critical diagnostic tool across numerous medical specialties, particularly in oncology. It is extensively used for the diagnosis, treatment planning, monitoring, and follow-up of various cancers. Key applications include identifying and monitoring brain tumors such as gliomas and primary CNS lymphoma, determining the extent of disease in cancers of the cervix, uterus, pelvis, prostate, and head and neck, and calculating tumor depth of invasion. For rectal cancer, MRI is specifically used to see how deep the cancer has grown and to check for spread to lymph nodes. It is also used to detect cancer in the abdomen and rectum, and in specialized exams like urograms to visualize the urinary tract.

Furthermore, MRI plays a central role in cancer surveillance and recurrence detection, being a standard test when recurrence is suspected and incorporated into specific follow-up protocols. The technique can be combined with other modalities; for instance, it can guide biopsies, sometimes in conjunction with ultrasound, or be combined with PET scans for more detailed imaging. The presence of surgical clips does not preclude a patient from having an MRI.<SEP>MRI is a type of imaging that may be included in the initial imaging to determine the extent of cervical cancer.<SEP>A diagnostic imaging method, with or without contrast, for evaluating the main tumor and neck.<SEP>Magnetic resonance imaging used to find lesions in the spine if cancer cells are in the spinal fluid or symptoms are present."}
