{"entity": "Surveillance", "type": "method", "description": "Surveillance, in the context of cancer care, is the comprehensive and ongoing process of follow-up monitoring conducted after a patient has completed initial treatment and entered remission. Its primary purpose is to detect any possible recurrence of cancer at the earliest, most treatable stage, thereby improving long-term health outcomes. This strategy is a standard phase of post-treatment management across various cancer types, specifically mentioned for anal, ovarian, cervical, and non-metastatic colon cancers.

The process involves a scheduled plan of regular follow-up care, which includes physical examinations and specific tests. Common components are digital rectal exams (DRE), lymph node examinations, proctoscopies or anoscopies, and various forms of medical imaging. The frequency of these checks is typically highest in the first few years. For anal cancer, a specific regimen may include DRE and lymph node exams every 3 to 6 months for 5 years and anoscopy every 6 to 12 months for 3 years.

