{"entity": "Basal Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, more common than squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, more common than squamous cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma (BCC) is an alternative name for basal cell skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, mentioned as a point of comparison for squamous cell skin cancer."}
{"entity": "Basal Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer. It is caused by damage to the DNA of basal cells, primarily from exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources. While it can occur in anyone, it is most frequently diagnosed in individuals with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, making fair skin a significant risk factor.\n\nThis cancer is characterized by its high treatability and curability, especially when detected and addressed early. A key clinical feature is that it rarely metastasizes, or spreads to other parts of the body. Accurate diagnostic testing is essential for confirming the diagnosis and for informing appropriate treatment planning.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a highly treatable and curable form of skin cancer.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer, also known as basal cell carcinoma (BCC), is the most common type of skin cancer, often treatable and curable when caught early.<SEP>Basal cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer that can happen to anyone but is most common in people with lighter skin, hair, or eyes, with specific lesion appearances."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Skin Cancer", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell skin cancer, also known as cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC), is the second most common type of skin cancer. It is highly treatable and often curable. This cancer typically begins as scaly patches on the skin and can develop from pre-cancerous lesions called actinic keratoses. It is most frequently caused by cumulative sun exposure over many years, with other major risk factors including indoor tanning and exposure to environmental toxins. It can also form within old wounds, burns, or scars.\n\nDiagnosis is confirmed through a skin biopsy. The disease is classified as local, regional, or metastatic, with the potential to spread to nearby lymph nodes. Treatment depends on the cancer's extent and risk classification. Primary treatments are surgical, including Mohs surgery and standard excision, often with lymph node assessment. Other options include radiation therapy and topical treatments. For advanced cases, systemic therapies such as chemotherapy, EGFR inhibitors, and PD-1 inhibitors are used.\n\nGiven its risk of recurrence and the increased risk of developing other skin cancers, patients require specific follow-up monitoring schedules after treatment, particularly for local and regional forms of the disease.<SEP>Squamous cell skin cancer is a type of cancer that can be treated with systemic therapy, including PD-1 inhibitors.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which a weakened immune system is a risk factor, requiring regular screening and diagnosis via biopsy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer; recurrent tumors of this type are considered high-risk, and it can start in areas of damaged skin."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It frequently develops in sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head, neck, and the vermilion lip, and occurs more often in individuals with lighter skin tones.\n\nThe primary and preferred treatment for low-risk cases that have not spread is surgery. Other treatment options include radiation therapy, cryotherapy, and topical therapies. Cases are classified as local when the cancer has not spread to nearby lymph nodes or other sites.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that can be treated by various surgical methods, including curettage and electrodesiccation, PDEMA/Mohs surgery, and standard surgical excision.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is the specific type of squamous cell skin cancer discussed, for which testing and treatment are described."}
{"entity": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (CSCC), also known as squamous cell skin cancer, is a very common type of skin cancer. It originates in the skin's squamous cells. CSCC occurs more frequently in individuals with lighter skin and is most commonly found on sun-exposed areas of the body, such as the head and neck. It can also form in scars or chronic wounds, a presentation that can be more difficult to treat.\n\nIn most cases, CSCC can be cured by the complete surgical removal of the tumor. For cases that are more advanced or difficult to treat, management strategies include targeted therapies, immunotherapy, and other forms of systemic therapy.<SEP>A type of skin cancer for which Mohs surgery is a recommended treatment option.<SEP>Cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is a type of skin cancer with low-risk, high-risk, and very high-risk classifications, for which various surgical treatments are recommended."}
{"entity": "Epidermis", "type": "concept", "description": "The epidermis is the outermost, top layer of the skin. Its primary functions are to provide a waterproof barrier for the body and to create skin color through the activity of specialized cells. The epidermis contains three main types of cells: squamous cells, basal cells, and melanocytes. It is also the layer where most skin cancers form. In a medical context, the epidermis is the specific layer of skin that is removed during a superficial shave biopsy procedure.<SEP>The epidermis is a layer of skin, and its upper part contains flat cells.<SEP>The epidermis is the top layer of the skin, providing a waterproof barrier and creating skin color; most skin cancers form in its cells.<SEP>The epidermis is the outer layer of skin containing the basal cell layer and the top layer where melanocytes are found.<SEP>The epidermis is the outermost layer of skin, providing a waterproof barrier, creating skin color, and where skin cancers often form.<SEP>The top layer of the skin, which is removed during a superficial skin shave biopsy."}
{"entity": "Local Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma", "type": "concept", "description": "Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is usually treated with surgery.<SEP>Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is usually treated with surgery.<SEP>Local cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma (CSCC) is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes."}
{"entity": "Nonmelanoma Skin Cancers", "type": "concept", "description": "Nonmelanoma skin cancers, or keratinocyte carcinomas, refer to basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers that behave differently from melanoma.<SEP>Nonmelanoma skin cancers, or keratinocyte carcinomas, refer to basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers that behave differently from melanoma.<SEP>Nonmelanoma skin cancers, also called keratinocyte carcinomas, is a category that includes basal cell and squamous cell skin cancers because they do not behave like melanoma."}
{"entity": "Tumor Type", "type": "concept", "description": "Tumor type refers to the specific classification of a cancer, with certain rare subtypes of squamous cell skin cancer being more likely to recur after treatment.<SEP>Tumor type is revealed by the pathology report based on molecular testing and is crucial for predicting disease course and planning treatment.<SEP>Tumor type is a classification determined through testing to guide treatment planning."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell Skin Cancer (CSCC)", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cell skin cancer is a type of skin cancer for which several treatments are described.<SEP>Squamous Cell Skin Cancer is a type of cancer that can be regional (spread to lymph nodes) or metastatic."}
{"entity": "Basal Cells", "type": "concept", "description": "Basal cells are a type of cell located in the basal cell layer, which is the lowest part of the epidermis. Their primary function is to constantly divide through mitosis, generating new cells. These new cells serve to replace the squamous cells on the skin's surface that are worn off through normal shedding. As these newly formed basal cells mature and move upward through the epidermal layers, they themselves differentiate and become squamous cells. This continuous cycle of cell division and differentiation is essential for skin renewal and repair. Furthermore, basal cells are clinically significant because basal cell skin cancer, a common form of skin cancer, originates when these cells undergo abnormal, uncontrolled growth.<SEP>Basal cells are cells found in the lower part of the epidermis that constantly divide to form new cells, replacing squamous cells on the skin's surface."}
{"entity": "CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "CSCC, or Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma, is a form of squamous cell skin cancer. It is a type of skin cancer that can metastasize and is characterized by varying risk levels, including low-risk forms and very high-risk local disease. A specific risk factor is its potential to grow in previously radiated areas of the skin.\n\nTreatment for CSCC is tailored based on its risk assessment. Surgical options are prominent, with Mohs micrographic surgery being a preferred treatment for very high-risk local tumors. Non-surgical treatments are also utilized, including radiation therapy (using electrons and photons), systemic therapies like the EGFR inhibitor Cetuximab, and PD-1 inhibitors. The choice of treatment, whether surgical or non-surgical, is recommended according to the cancer's risk level. A noted specific risk of treatment, particularly when the cancer is located near the eye, is the potential development of cataracts from radiation therapy.<SEP>CSCC is a type of cancer that can be treated with radiation therapy methods like EBRT and brachytherapy.<SEP>CSCC refers to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, a type of squamous cell skin cancer that may be treated with systemic therapy and radiation."}
{"entity": "Squamous Cell", "type": "concept", "description": "Squamous cells are thin, flat cells found in the top layer of the skin (epidermis) and other body areas like the lungs, thyroid, and esophagus."}
