{"entity": "Local CSCC", "type": "concept", "description": "Local CSCC, which stands for Local Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma (also commonly referred to as squamous cell skin cancer), is a form of skin cancer that is confined to its original site. It is specifically defined by the absence of spread, or metastasis, to nearby lymph nodes. In some descriptions, this local confinement is further clarified as cancer that has not spread beyond the original site.\n\nThe primary and most common treatment for Local CSCC is surgical removal. Following treatment, this diagnosis necessitates adherence to specific, structured follow-up monitoring schedules. The frequency and nature of these required monitoring exams are directly influenced by the local, non-metastatic status of the cancer.<SEP>Local CSCC is a type of squamous cell skin cancer that is confined to its original site and may be monitored with imaging tests.<SEP>Local CSCC is squamous cell skin cancer that has not spread to nearby lymph nodes and is most often treated with surgery."}
