{"entity": "Systemic Therapy", "type": "method", "description": "Systemic therapy is a broad category of cancer treatment that involves the administration of medicines, such as drugs or biological agents, which travel via the bloodstream to affect cells throughout the entire body. This distinguishes it from localized treatments like surgery or radiation. The primary types of systemic therapy include chemotherapy, targeted therapy, immunotherapy, and endocrine therapy. It is administered by a Medical Oncologist or oncology nurses, often intravenously.\n\nIts applications are varied and depend on the specific cancer and its stage. Systemic therapy can be used as a primary treatment, administered before surgery (neoadjuvant) to shrink tumors, after surgery (adjuvant) to eliminate remaining cancer cells, in combination with radiation therapy, or when surgery is not possible. It is particularly crucial for metastatic, recurrent, or advanced disease, where it is a standard treatment.\n\nSystemic therapy is used to treat a wide range of cancers, including but not limited to cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, basal cell skin cancer, cervical cancer, bladder cancer, thyroid cancer, anal cancer, acute myeloid leukemia (AML), and acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL). For cancers like cutaneous squamous cell carcinoma, it is typically reserved for cases where the disease has spread.\n\nBecause it affects cells throughout the body, systemic therapy impacts both cancerous and healthy cells, leading to potential side effects such as hair loss, fatigue, nausea, and low blood cell counts. For metastatic or advanced disease, its effectiveness is commonly monitored through medical imaging to assess the cancer's response.<SEP>Systemic therapy works throughout the body to treat cancer and includes chemotherapy, targeted therapy, and immunotherapy.<SEP>Systemic therapy refers to treatments like chemotherapy that affect the whole body, for which side effects must be managed.<SEP>Systemic Therapy is a treatment method for cancer that includes chemotherapy and immunotherapy, administered by a Medical Oncologist."}
